1
00:00:31,583 --> 00:00:33,165
(RAIN PATTERING)

2
00:00:35,041 --> 00:00:36,707
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

3
00:01:24,375 --> 00:01:25,624
BOY: (ON RECORD)
In order to show you how

4
00:01:25,708 --> 00:01:28,207
a big symphony
orchestra is put together,

5
00:01:28,291 --> 00:01:31,374
Benjamin Britten
has written a big piece of music,

6
00:01:31,458 --> 00:01:33,207
which is made up
of smaller pieces

7
00:01:33,291 --> 00:01:36,290
that show you all
the separate parts of the orchestra.

8
00:01:36,375 --> 00:01:39,165
These smaller pieces
are called variations,

9
00:01:39,250 --> 00:01:42,749
which means different ways
of playing the same tune.

10
00:01:42,875 --> 00:01:46,082
First of all,
he lets us hear the tune or the theme,

11
00:01:46,166 --> 00:01:47,290
which is a beautiful melody

12
00:01:47,375 --> 00:01:50,749
by the much older
British composer Henry Purcell.

13
00:01:50,833 --> 00:01:55,290
Here is Purcell's theme
played by the whole orchestra together.

14
00:01:55,375 --> 00:01:57,957
(ORCHESTRA PLAYING)

15
00:02:16,375 --> 00:02:18,124
(LIGHTNING CRACKING)

16
00:02:24,541 --> 00:02:28,499
Now, Mr. Britten lets you hear
the four different families of the orchestra

17
00:02:28,583 --> 00:02:31,540
playing the same Purcell theme
in different ways.

18
00:02:31,625 --> 00:02:33,415
First, we hear
the woodwind family.

19
00:02:33,500 --> 00:02:37,165
The flutes, the oboes,
the clarinets and the bassoons.

20
00:02:37,250 --> 00:02:39,040
(INSTRUMENTS PLAYING)

21
00:02:53,541 --> 00:02:55,499
(CHILDREN LAUGHING)

22
00:02:59,458 --> 00:03:01,374
Here comes the brass family.

23
00:03:01,458 --> 00:03:04,749
The trumpets, the horns,
the trombones and the tubas.

24
00:03:07,250 --> 00:03:09,540
(INSTRUMENTS PLAYING)

25
00:03:10,875 --> 00:03:12,249
One to four.

26
00:03:15,666 --> 00:03:17,165
(WATER RUNNING)

27
00:03:23,625 --> 00:03:27,665
BOY: Now, Mr. Britten arranges the Purcell theme
for the string family.

28
00:03:27,750 --> 00:03:28,790
I'm sick of this rain.

29
00:03:28,875 --> 00:03:33,290
BOY: The violins,
the violas, the cellos and the double basses.

30
00:03:33,375 --> 00:03:35,749
And of course, the harp.

31
00:03:36,125 --> 00:03:37,915
(INSTRUMENTS PLAYING)

32
00:03:56,750 --> 00:03:59,124
And finally
the percussion family,

33
00:03:59,208 --> 00:04:02,499
all those drums and gongs
and things you hit.

34
00:04:02,958 --> 00:04:05,374
(INSTRUMENTS PLAYING)

35
00:04:06,208 --> 00:04:08,665
After this, you will
hear the theme by Purcell

36
00:04:08,750 --> 00:04:12,665
played once more in its original
form by all four families together.

37
00:04:12,750 --> 00:04:15,040
That is, the whole orchestra.

38
00:04:15,125 --> 00:04:17,040
(ORCHESTRA PLAYING)

39
00:04:38,666 --> 00:04:41,040
NARRATOR: This is
the island of New Penzance.

40
00:04:42,416 --> 00:04:44,290
16 miles long.

41
00:04:45,458 --> 00:04:48,457
Forested with
old-growth pine and maple.

42
00:04:49,625 --> 00:04:52,207
Criss-crossed by
shallow tidal creeks.

43
00:04:53,333 --> 00:04:55,707
Chickchaw territory.

44
00:04:56,250 --> 00:04:57,290
There are no
paved roads, but...

45
00:04:57,458 --> 00:04:58,540
(PLANE ZOOMING OVERHEAD)

46
00:04:58,625 --> 00:05:00,582
Here comes Jed
with the mail.

47
00:05:00,666 --> 00:05:04,707
But instead many
miles of intersecting footpaths and dirt trails,

48
00:05:04,791 --> 00:05:07,832
and a ferry that
runs twice daily from Stone Cove.

49
00:05:08,791 --> 00:05:12,165
The year is 1 965.

50
00:05:13,208 --> 00:05:16,207
We are on the far edge
of Black Beacon Sound,

51
00:05:16,291 --> 00:05:18,957
famous for the ferocious
and well-documented storm,

52
00:05:19,041 --> 00:05:22,290
which will
strike from the east on the 5th of September.

53
00:05:23,041 --> 00:05:25,540
In three days' time.

54
00:05:26,583 --> 00:05:28,749
(BLOWS)

55
00:05:33,041 --> 00:05:34,082
(SPITS)

56
00:05:41,750 --> 00:05:42,957
Morning, Gadge.

57
00:05:43,041 --> 00:05:44,332
Morning, sir.

58
00:05:53,125 --> 00:05:55,332
Deluca,
latrine inspection.

59
00:06:04,041 --> 00:06:05,374
Good.

60
00:06:07,500 --> 00:06:09,707
Roosevelt,
how's that lanyard coming?

61
00:06:10,708 --> 00:06:11,874
Horrible.

62
00:06:15,958 --> 00:06:17,707
Skotak,
what's all this lumber for?

63
00:06:17,791 --> 00:06:19,124
We're building a tree house.

64
00:06:19,208 --> 00:06:20,540
-Where?
-Right here.

65
00:06:23,250 --> 00:06:26,499
That's not a safe altitude.
Why is it up so high?

66
00:06:26,583 --> 00:06:28,665
If someone falls from there,
that's a guaranteed death.

67
00:06:28,750 --> 00:06:29,874
Well, where would
you have built it?

68
00:06:30,625 --> 00:06:32,124
Lower.

69
00:06:38,125 --> 00:06:39,790
Nickleby?
What are you doing?

70
00:06:39,875 --> 00:06:41,499
Pest control.
Burning some ants.

71
00:06:41,583 --> 00:06:43,249
Spot check.

72
00:06:45,291 --> 00:06:46,999
Your socks are down,
your shirt tails are untucked,

73
00:06:47,083 --> 00:06:48,499
your trousers are
not properly pressed.

74
00:06:48,583 --> 00:06:51,040
You are reported for
a uniform violation.

75
00:06:54,083 --> 00:06:55,290
How many rockets
you up to, Panagle?

76
00:06:55,375 --> 00:06:56,415
Sixteen and a half, sir.

77
00:06:56,500 --> 00:06:57,790
Is that enough
for the Hullabaloo?

78
00:06:57,875 --> 00:07:00,457
Izod, go fetch another pint of
gunpowder from the armory shed.

79
00:07:00,541 --> 00:07:01,915
Redford! Halt!
I saw that!

80
00:07:02,083 --> 00:07:03,457
(ENGINE IDLING)

81
00:07:03,541 --> 00:07:05,040
-How fast were you just going?
-Safety test, sir.

82
00:07:05,125 --> 00:07:06,165
Come again?

83
00:07:06,250 --> 00:07:07,499
The vehicle
appears to be in good working order,

84
00:07:07,583 --> 00:07:08,665
I'm just checking if...

85
00:07:08,750 --> 00:07:10,165
Reckless cycling.
Second warning.

86
00:07:10,250 --> 00:07:12,040
Next time,
I take away the keys.

87
00:07:14,083 --> 00:07:15,749
Morning, Chef.

88
00:07:15,833 --> 00:07:17,332
(BELL RINGING)

89
00:07:25,041 --> 00:07:25,915
(WHISTLE BLOWING)

90
00:07:26,083 --> 00:07:26,957
MAN: Clear!

91
00:07:27,041 --> 00:07:28,582
(BOYS MARCHING)

92
00:07:38,916 --> 00:07:41,040
Who's missing?

93
00:07:41,125 --> 00:07:43,082
-Who's missing?
-Shakusky.

94
00:07:43,166 --> 00:07:46,290
-Shakusky.
-Shakusky.

95
00:07:46,375 --> 00:07:47,957
Shakusky! Breakfast!

96
00:07:48,750 --> 00:07:50,249
(PANTING)

97
00:07:54,500 --> 00:07:56,582
Shakusky, you in there?

98
00:07:57,958 --> 00:07:59,415
Sam?

99
00:08:02,666 --> 00:08:04,082
It's zipped from the inside.

100
00:08:29,875 --> 00:08:32,207
Jiminy Cricket,
he flew the coop.

101
00:08:33,458 --> 00:08:35,874
(LIGHT ROCK MUSIC
PLAYING OVER RADIO)

102
00:08:41,208 --> 00:08:42,915
(BELL RINGING)

103
00:08:45,166 --> 00:08:46,540
(DOOR OPENS)

104
00:08:51,750 --> 00:08:53,624
Hello, this is
Captain Sharp, over.

105
00:08:53,708 --> 00:08:57,207
Captain Sharp, this is Randall
Ward over at Camp Ivanhoe. Over.

106
00:08:57,291 --> 00:08:59,332
Morning, Randy.
What can I do for you? Over.

107
00:08:59,416 --> 00:09:03,999
I'm not sure exactly.
I've got an escaped Khaki Scout. Over.

108
00:09:05,708 --> 00:09:07,124
What does that mean? Over.

109
00:09:07,208 --> 00:09:08,832
One of my boys
seems to have stolen

110
00:09:08,916 --> 00:09:10,832
a miniature canoe and
some fishing tackle,

111
00:09:10,916 --> 00:09:13,874
1 0 pounds of sundries,
two bedrolls, plus an air rifle.

112
00:09:13,958 --> 00:09:15,999
And disappeared. Over.

113
00:09:16,083 --> 00:09:17,457
Any idea why? Over.

114
00:09:17,541 --> 00:09:20,707
No. He left me
a letter of resignation. Over.

115
00:09:20,791 --> 00:09:21,999
SAM: Dear Scout Master Ward,

116
00:09:22,083 --> 00:09:24,790
I am very sad to inform you
I can no longer be involved

117
00:09:24,875 --> 00:09:26,707
with the Khaki
Scouts of North America.

118
00:09:26,791 --> 00:09:28,999
The rest of the troop
will probably be glad to hear this.

119
00:09:29,083 --> 00:09:30,124
It is not your fault.

120
00:09:30,208 --> 00:09:31,790
Best wishes, Sam Shakusky.

121
00:09:33,583 --> 00:09:36,957
Well, I guess we better
notify his folks. Over.

122
00:09:37,041 --> 00:09:39,290
Okay. Over and out.

123
00:09:48,666 --> 00:09:49,915
(BUZZING)

124
00:09:54,583 --> 00:09:55,624
Hello, Diane.

125
00:09:55,708 --> 00:09:58,374
Becky, I have your
person-to-person from Chesterfield.

126
00:09:58,458 --> 00:09:59,624
Hold the line, please.

127
00:09:59,708 --> 00:10:01,374
(RINGING)

128
00:10:01,458 --> 00:10:02,499
Hello?

129
00:10:02,583 --> 00:10:04,332
Hello, sir.
This is Captain Sharp.

130
00:10:04,416 --> 00:10:07,749
Yes, sir. I received your
message. Thank you very much.

131
00:10:07,833 --> 00:10:11,290
In fact, we've come to
a decision, as a family,

132
00:10:11,375 --> 00:10:15,540
because this is only the most recent
incident involving Sam's troubles,

133
00:10:15,625 --> 00:10:18,749
and it's just not
fair to the others, so, unfortunately,

134
00:10:18,833 --> 00:10:22,207
we can't invite him
back at this time.

135
00:10:24,625 --> 00:10:28,374
There's no cause
for alarm, sir. We'll find him.

136
00:10:28,458 --> 00:10:31,165
We're simply notifying you
as a matter of protocol and so on.

137
00:10:31,500 --> 00:10:34,540
I understand that.
I'm notifying you of the situation on my end.

138
00:10:35,583 --> 00:10:38,582
I'm confused by
that statement. You can't invite him back?

139
00:10:39,166 --> 00:10:42,540
I'm afraid not.
He's a good boy. He's got a good heart.

140
00:10:42,625 --> 00:10:45,332
But it's just not fair
to the others, you see?

141
00:10:46,208 --> 00:10:48,290
He's emotionally disturbed.

142
00:10:51,958 --> 00:10:53,665
Am I speaking
with Sam's father?

143
00:10:55,541 --> 00:10:57,415
No, sir.

144
00:10:57,500 --> 00:10:59,707
Sam's parents passed away
a number of years ago.

145
00:10:59,791 --> 00:11:02,832
We're Mr. and
Mrs. Billingsley. We're foster parents.

146
00:11:03,416 --> 00:11:06,040
Sam's been with
us since last June.

147
00:11:06,125 --> 00:11:08,957
Excuse me, sir.
This is Scout Master Ward speaking.

148
00:11:09,041 --> 00:11:10,790
Are you implying
that Sam is an orphan?

149
00:11:11,375 --> 00:11:13,457
Well, it's a known fact.
Of course he is.

150
00:11:13,916 --> 00:11:15,665
Well, why the hell
doesn't it say so in the register?

151
00:11:15,750 --> 00:11:16,832
Excuse my language.

152
00:11:17,750 --> 00:11:19,165
I don't know.
What register?

153
00:11:21,833 --> 00:11:23,874
We sent him a letter.
It should reach you presently.

154
00:11:25,291 --> 00:11:28,040
Mr. Billingsley,
I've got an escaped Khaki Scout.

155
00:11:28,125 --> 00:11:30,415
We are notifying you
as a matter of protocol.

156
00:11:30,500 --> 00:11:33,707
You say you can't
invite him back? You say that he's an orphan?

157
00:11:34,375 --> 00:11:36,040
I don't understand
how that works.

158
00:11:36,791 --> 00:11:38,665
What am I supposed
to do with him?

159
00:11:39,625 --> 00:11:42,374
That's up to social services.
They'll be in touch with you.

160
00:11:42,458 --> 00:11:45,249
They'll look after Sam.
Good luck to you.

161
00:11:48,666 --> 00:11:49,874
(SIGHS)

162
00:11:53,666 --> 00:11:54,790
You have your orders.

163
00:11:54,875 --> 00:11:56,832
Use the orienteering
and path-finding skills

164
00:11:56,916 --> 00:11:58,499
that you've been
practicing all summer.

165
00:11:58,583 --> 00:12:01,457
Let's find our man,
bring him safely back to camp.

166
00:12:01,541 --> 00:12:03,749
Remember, this isn't
just a search party,

167
00:12:03,833 --> 00:12:05,957
it's a chance to do
some first class Scouting.

168
00:12:06,041 --> 00:12:08,207
Any questions?

169
00:12:08,291 --> 00:12:09,415
Lazy-Eye?

170
00:12:09,500 --> 00:12:11,082
What's your real job, sir?

171
00:12:11,166 --> 00:12:12,957
-I'm a math teacher. Why?
-What grade?

172
00:12:13,041 --> 00:12:14,749
-Eighth.
-You need a PhD for that?

173
00:12:14,833 --> 00:12:16,165
Lazy-Eye, no,
but you know what,

174
00:12:16,250 --> 00:12:18,790
we're actually in the middle of something
here, in case you didn't notice.

175
00:12:18,875 --> 00:12:20,999
One of our Scouts is missing
and that's a crisis.

176
00:12:21,083 --> 00:12:22,124
Anybody else?
Redford?

177
00:12:22,250 --> 00:12:23,290
What if he resists?

178
00:12:23,375 --> 00:12:24,457
-Who?
-Shakusky.

179
00:12:24,541 --> 00:12:25,582
Are we allowed to
use force on him?

180
00:12:25,666 --> 00:12:29,832
No, you're not.
This is a non-violent, rescue operation.

181
00:12:29,916 --> 00:12:33,290
Your mission is to find him,
not to hurt him under any circumstances.

182
00:12:33,375 --> 00:12:35,249
Am I making
myself understood?

183
00:12:35,333 --> 00:12:37,124
-ALL: (MURMURING) Yes.
-Good.

184
00:12:38,666 --> 00:12:41,290
I'm going to change my answer,
in fact, this is my real job.

185
00:12:41,375 --> 00:12:44,957
Scout Master Troop 55.
I'm a math teacher on the side.

186
00:12:46,041 --> 00:12:47,790
Be leery out there. Okay?

187
00:12:47,875 --> 00:12:49,290
Now let's get started.
Who's got Snoopy?

188
00:12:49,375 --> 00:12:50,707
SKOTAK: Right here.

189
00:12:51,208 --> 00:12:53,124
RANDALL: Give him the scent.

190
00:12:56,916 --> 00:12:58,957
I heard he ran away
because his family died.

191
00:12:59,333 --> 00:13:01,332
I heard he
never had any family in the first place.

192
00:13:01,416 --> 00:13:02,749
That's probably
why he's crazy.

193
00:13:02,833 --> 00:13:03,957
I'll tell you one thing,

194
00:13:04,041 --> 00:13:06,790
if we find him, I'm not going to be the
one who forgot to bring a weapon.

195
00:13:06,875 --> 00:13:08,832
(SCOFFS) Me, neither.

196
00:13:40,291 --> 00:13:41,374
(INAUDIBLE)

197
00:13:57,166 --> 00:13:59,957
Camp Ivanhoe, that's all the way
across the other side of the island.

198
00:14:00,041 --> 00:14:01,290
You really think
a 12-year-old boy

199
00:14:01,375 --> 00:14:03,332
could row this far
in a miniature canoe?

200
00:14:03,416 --> 00:14:04,457
Most likely not.

201
00:14:04,541 --> 00:14:05,999
It is possible, Counselor.

202
00:14:06,083 --> 00:14:08,290
I disagree, Counselor.
It would take him three days, at least.

203
00:14:08,375 --> 00:14:09,832
I don't think so.
Two days, maximum.

204
00:14:09,916 --> 00:14:12,165
-Well, I'm not going to argue about it.
-Be that as it may,

205
00:14:12,250 --> 00:14:14,207
-will you let me know if you see anything unusual?
-Yup.

206
00:15:23,250 --> 00:15:26,124
RANDALL: Scout Master's log,
September 2nd.

207
00:15:26,208 --> 00:15:28,624
First day of search
party for Sam Shakusky.

208
00:15:29,000 --> 00:15:30,290
Morale is extremely low,

209
00:15:30,375 --> 00:15:31,415
in part, I suppose,

210
00:15:31,500 --> 00:15:33,790
because Sam is
the least popular Scout in the troop.

211
00:15:34,791 --> 00:15:36,249
By a significant margin.

212
00:15:37,875 --> 00:15:40,624
I'm confused
and I'm worried.

213
00:15:40,916 --> 00:15:42,124
(SIGHS)

214
00:15:42,208 --> 00:15:44,624
Please let us
find him tomorrow.

215
00:15:44,708 --> 00:15:48,040
Please don't let
him fall off a cliff,

216
00:15:48,125 --> 00:15:50,332
or drown in the goddamn
lake or something.

217
00:15:50,416 --> 00:15:51,999
A terrible day
at Camp Ivanhoe.

218
00:15:52,083 --> 00:15:53,707
(BREATHES DEEPLY)

219
00:15:55,208 --> 00:15:56,874
Let's hope
tomorrow's better.

220
00:17:16,958 --> 00:17:18,457
(ACTOR SPEAKING)

221
00:17:23,875 --> 00:17:26,124
One Year earlier

222
00:17:26,208 --> 00:17:28,082
(ORCHESTRA PLAYING)

223
00:17:38,708 --> 00:17:40,290
(ACTORS GASPING)

224
00:17:57,583 --> 00:17:59,082
(GIRL SINGING)

225
00:18:09,208 --> 00:18:11,207
(WHISPERING INDISTINCTLY)

226
00:18:23,166 --> 00:18:24,957
(PLAYING OUT OF TUNE)

227
00:18:41,916 --> 00:18:43,207
(GIRLS GIGGLING)

228
00:18:45,458 --> 00:18:47,749
(MURMURING INDISTINCTLY)

229
00:18:50,708 --> 00:18:52,457
(SAM CLEARS THROAT)

230
00:18:55,250 --> 00:18:56,457
What kind of bird are you?

231
00:18:57,458 --> 00:18:59,707
I'm a sparrow,
she's a dove...

232
00:18:59,791 --> 00:19:03,957
No. I said,
what kind of bird are you?

233
00:19:07,166 --> 00:19:08,415
I'm a raven.

234
00:19:09,791 --> 00:19:10,957
Boys aren't
allowed in here.

235
00:19:12,541 --> 00:19:13,707
I'll be leaving soon.

236
00:19:16,791 --> 00:19:18,040
What happened to your hand?

237
00:19:20,125 --> 00:19:21,832
I got hit in the mirror.

238
00:19:21,916 --> 00:19:23,665
Really, how did that happen?

239
00:19:24,958 --> 00:19:26,874
I lost my temper at myself.

240
00:19:30,375 --> 00:19:31,457
What's your name?

241
00:19:31,541 --> 00:19:32,790
Sam. What's yours?

242
00:19:33,250 --> 00:19:34,624
I'm Suzy.

243
00:19:37,291 --> 00:19:38,707
It's not polite to stare.

244
00:19:39,666 --> 00:19:41,415
Birds, ready?
Who are you?

245
00:19:41,500 --> 00:19:43,040
Where did you come from?
Go back to your seat.

246
00:19:44,958 --> 00:19:46,290
(GIGGLING)

247
00:19:49,208 --> 00:19:50,915
He likes you.

248
00:19:53,083 --> 00:19:54,874
(ALL SINGING)

249
00:20:24,375 --> 00:20:25,540
Were you followed?

250
00:20:28,041 --> 00:20:29,540
-I doubt it.
-Good.

251
00:20:29,625 --> 00:20:30,665
(MEOWING)

252
00:20:32,083 --> 00:20:33,332
Is that a cat in there?

253
00:20:41,625 --> 00:20:43,832
-Can you read a map?
-Uh-huh.

254
00:20:44,208 --> 00:20:46,415
I do cartography.

255
00:20:46,500 --> 00:20:48,624
I feel we should
go halfway today, and halfway tomorrow

256
00:20:48,708 --> 00:20:50,124
since you're a less
experienced hiker,

257
00:20:50,208 --> 00:20:52,249
and you're wearing
Sunday school shoes.

258
00:20:52,333 --> 00:20:53,374
They're not really
Sunday school shoes.

259
00:20:53,458 --> 00:20:54,499
Here.

260
00:20:54,583 --> 00:20:55,624
Oh, thank you.

261
00:20:58,208 --> 00:20:59,665
Here's where
we are right now.

262
00:20:59,750 --> 00:21:01,874
I'd like to pitch
camp here by 1600,

263
00:21:01,958 --> 00:21:03,790
which means 4:00.
How does that sound?

264
00:21:03,875 --> 00:21:05,790
-Fine.
-You want some beefjerky?

265
00:21:05,875 --> 00:21:07,290
-Okay.
-Let's go.

266
00:21:20,125 --> 00:21:21,499
Are you thirsty?

267
00:21:21,583 --> 00:21:22,957
No, thank you.

268
00:21:23,041 --> 00:21:25,124
Well, if your throat
gets parched,

269
00:21:25,208 --> 00:21:26,999
stick a pebble in your
mouth and suck on it.

270
00:21:27,083 --> 00:21:28,957
You can quench your thirst
with the spit, supposedly.

271
00:21:29,500 --> 00:21:30,540
Mmm-hmm.

272
00:21:31,208 --> 00:21:34,415
Sometimes I stick leaves on my
hair. It helps cool your head down.

273
00:21:34,500 --> 00:21:35,540
Hmm. That's a good idea.

274
00:21:35,625 --> 00:21:37,957
It might also help if
you didn't wear a fur hat.

275
00:21:38,041 --> 00:21:39,999
Yeah. True.

276
00:21:41,291 --> 00:21:44,582
You can go ahead.
Be careful.

277
00:21:55,708 --> 00:21:57,457
Here's a trick,
throw pine needles in the air

278
00:21:57,541 --> 00:21:59,457
and you can see
which direction the wind is blowing.

279
00:22:03,750 --> 00:22:05,082
(HESITANTLY) Which way?

280
00:22:07,875 --> 00:22:08,999
I guess it
doesn't really matter,

281
00:22:09,083 --> 00:22:10,374
just as long as we
cover our tracks.

282
00:22:21,875 --> 00:22:23,874
You smell like perfume.

283
00:22:23,958 --> 00:22:25,374
Oh, it's my mother's.

284
00:22:26,041 --> 00:22:27,790
Hmm. Hmm.

285
00:22:38,291 --> 00:22:40,165
I brought water, too.

286
00:22:43,500 --> 00:22:45,165
-You wait here.
-Okay.

287
00:22:46,416 --> 00:22:47,790
Be right back.

288
00:22:49,750 --> 00:22:50,874
(CAT MEOWS)

289
00:22:50,958 --> 00:22:52,165
Watch your head!

290
00:23:02,250 --> 00:23:03,624
Where the hell is it?

291
00:23:10,708 --> 00:23:11,999
Found it!

292
00:23:22,791 --> 00:23:23,915
It's ready.

293
00:23:24,875 --> 00:23:27,374
He knows someone's
watching him.

294
00:23:27,458 --> 00:23:31,040
I agree. Wait.
Why do you say that?

295
00:23:32,416 --> 00:23:35,249
Mmm... I don't know,
I just think he can feel us.

296
00:23:40,666 --> 00:23:42,207
Follow me.

297
00:24:09,666 --> 00:24:11,290
SAM: How strong of
a swimmer are you?

298
00:24:11,375 --> 00:24:14,124
Pretty good.
I broke our school record for the backstroke.

299
00:24:14,208 --> 00:24:17,790
Okay. Well, I'm not that strong of a
swimmer, so I wear a life preserver.

300
00:24:17,875 --> 00:24:18,915
(CLEARS THROAT)

301
00:24:23,708 --> 00:24:24,832
Watch out for turtles.

302
00:24:24,916 --> 00:24:27,415
They'll bite you
if you put your fingers down their mouths.

303
00:24:27,500 --> 00:24:29,082
Okay.

304
00:24:29,166 --> 00:24:30,874
Let me see if I
can catch this one.

305
00:24:33,708 --> 00:24:35,207
Feel something.

306
00:24:40,000 --> 00:24:41,124
Hmm...

307
00:24:41,208 --> 00:24:42,499
Somebody wrote on him.

308
00:24:43,625 --> 00:24:45,540
(STAMMERING)
The stick's moving.

309
00:24:45,625 --> 00:24:46,790
You got one!

310
00:24:48,041 --> 00:24:50,790
Fish on hook!
Reel him in, slowly.

311
00:25:00,583 --> 00:25:01,665
Mmm.

312
00:25:04,500 --> 00:25:07,499
Very good.
You know a lot about camping, don't you?

313
00:25:08,333 --> 00:25:12,457
I'm a Khaki Scout. It's what I'm trained
for. Well, anyway, I used to be.

314
00:25:13,500 --> 00:25:16,957
Maybe we can feed your cat
the guts and eyeballs.

315
00:25:17,041 --> 00:25:18,707
Oh, that's okay.
He only eats kitten food.

316
00:25:20,083 --> 00:25:21,124
Oh.

317
00:25:21,833 --> 00:25:24,540
What else did you bring?
Maybe we can make an inventory.

318
00:25:25,375 --> 00:25:26,499
Okay.

319
00:25:37,041 --> 00:25:38,082
Go ahead.

320
00:25:38,375 --> 00:25:41,124
This is my record player.
It works with batteries.

321
00:25:41,208 --> 00:25:43,582
Well, actually,
it belongs to my little brother, Lionel.

322
00:25:43,666 --> 00:25:45,124
-I left him a note.
-Okay.

323
00:25:45,208 --> 00:25:47,082
-Do you like music?
-Yeah.

324
00:25:48,166 --> 00:25:50,165
This is my
favorite record album.

325
00:25:50,250 --> 00:25:52,249
My godmother gave it
to me for my birthday.

326
00:25:52,333 --> 00:25:54,082
She lives in France.

327
00:25:56,125 --> 00:25:59,499
These are my books.
I like stories with magic powers in them.

328
00:25:59,583 --> 00:26:02,040
Either in kingdoms on Earth
or on foreign planets.

329
00:26:02,125 --> 00:26:05,249
Usually, I prefer
a girl hero, but not always.

330
00:26:05,333 --> 00:26:07,457
I couldn't bring them all
because it got too heavy.

331
00:26:07,541 --> 00:26:08,665
You can borrow any you want.

332
00:26:08,750 --> 00:26:09,790
Thank you.

333
00:26:09,875 --> 00:26:14,749
I also brought
my lefty scissors because I'm left-handed,

334
00:26:14,833 --> 00:26:19,374
some rubber bands,
extra batteries, my toothbrush,

335
00:26:19,458 --> 00:26:20,540
and my binoculars,
as you know.

336
00:26:20,625 --> 00:26:21,665
Yeah.

337
00:26:21,750 --> 00:26:23,957
I forgot my comb.
But I'll use my fingers.

338
00:26:25,125 --> 00:26:26,332
(SIGHS)

339
00:26:29,291 --> 00:26:30,374
Huh.

340
00:26:32,791 --> 00:26:36,665
Wait, these are all
library books.

341
00:26:36,750 --> 00:26:40,665
In my school, you're only
allowed to check out one at a time.

342
00:26:41,083 --> 00:26:43,957
Some of these are
going to be overdue.

343
00:26:45,875 --> 00:26:47,082
Do you steal?

344
00:26:49,666 --> 00:26:51,374
Why? You're not poor.

345
00:26:52,541 --> 00:26:56,249
I might turn some of
them back in one day. I haven't decided yet.

346
00:26:56,333 --> 00:26:59,915
I know it's bad. I think I just took
them to have a secret to keep.

347
00:27:00,000 --> 00:27:01,665
Anyway,
for some reason,

348
00:27:01,750 --> 00:27:03,415
it makes me feel in
a better mood sometimes.

349
00:27:04,916 --> 00:27:06,624
Are you depressed?

350
00:27:08,375 --> 00:27:09,624
How come?

351
00:27:09,708 --> 00:27:11,999
Well, I can show you
an example, if you'd like,

352
00:27:13,500 --> 00:27:15,749
but it doesn't make
me feel very good.

353
00:27:15,833 --> 00:27:20,165
Anyway, I found this
on top of our refrigerator.

354
00:27:21,541 --> 00:27:22,582
Does that mean you?

355
00:27:23,750 --> 00:27:25,124
I think so.

356
00:27:26,250 --> 00:27:27,374
(SNORTS)

357
00:27:29,666 --> 00:27:30,707
Are you laughing?

358
00:27:34,083 --> 00:27:35,124
It's not funny.

359
00:27:38,875 --> 00:27:41,415
You really know
how to make friends.

360
00:28:00,583 --> 00:28:01,624
I'm sorry.

361
00:28:02,916 --> 00:28:04,790
Oh. It's okay.

362
00:28:05,125 --> 00:28:06,790
I'm on your side.

363
00:28:08,250 --> 00:28:09,582
I know.

364
00:28:14,666 --> 00:28:16,040
Thank you.

365
00:28:20,166 --> 00:28:22,582
Which one's the best?

366
00:28:22,666 --> 00:28:26,832
"His eyes downcast, his kingdom in
ruins, Mynar pressed his heavy paw

367
00:28:26,916 --> 00:28:28,874
"through the rippling surface
of the cool shallows

368
00:28:28,958 --> 00:28:30,582
"and down to its stone floor.

369
00:28:30,666 --> 00:28:33,749
"My people once were led
by a great and noble beast

370
00:28:33,833 --> 00:28:37,040
"and I no longer
see his face in this reflection.'

371
00:28:50,583 --> 00:28:51,665
(SIGHS)

372
00:28:51,750 --> 00:28:54,999
"Meanwhile,
on the Plains of Tabitha, Francine rested.

373
00:28:55,083 --> 00:28:57,040
"There would be
another time for war."

374
00:28:57,458 --> 00:28:59,749
(SOFT MUSIC PLAYING)

375
00:28:59,833 --> 00:29:02,540
Suzy! Dinner! I'm not
going to say it again.

376
00:29:04,875 --> 00:29:06,332
Where's your sister?

377
00:29:06,416 --> 00:29:10,749
I don't know, but she borrowed
my record player for 1 0 days without asking.

378
00:29:10,833 --> 00:29:13,499
What does that mean?

379
00:29:13,583 --> 00:29:15,999
SUZY: Dear Lionel, I need
to use your record player.

380
00:29:16,083 --> 00:29:19,624
I will give it back
in 1 0 days or less. Do not tell Mom. Or Dad.

381
00:29:19,708 --> 00:29:22,915
I will replace the batteries when I
return. Signed, Suzy Bishop.

382
00:29:25,875 --> 00:29:27,457
Walt! Where the hell are you?

383
00:29:27,541 --> 00:29:28,665
Right here!

384
00:29:28,750 --> 00:29:30,665
Why are you cursing at me?

385
00:29:30,750 --> 00:29:33,415
Does it concern you that
your daughter's just run away from home?

386
00:29:36,583 --> 00:29:37,874
That's a loaded question.

387
00:29:38,375 --> 00:29:39,707
Come down and read this.

388
00:29:40,375 --> 00:29:42,999
BECKY: (OVER RADIO) Scout Master Ward
confirms they've had no luck.

389
00:29:43,083 --> 00:29:44,124
They're going home for...

390
00:29:44,208 --> 00:29:45,249
(RADIO CLICKS OFF)

391
00:29:47,250 --> 00:29:48,290
Who's there?

392
00:29:53,333 --> 00:29:56,082
Good evening.
Sorry to startle you.

393
00:29:56,166 --> 00:29:58,707
What are you doing here?
Nobody called the police.

394
00:29:58,791 --> 00:30:01,082
I know. Uh...
I know.

395
00:30:01,166 --> 00:30:03,582
The search party's
not over yet. In other words...

396
00:30:03,666 --> 00:30:05,832
Suzy's missing, too!
Go find her.

397
00:30:08,833 --> 00:30:11,082
MAN: (OVER RADIO) The tropical cyclone,
which originated last week

398
00:30:11,166 --> 00:30:13,999
off the coast of
British Honduras, has intensified rapidly

399
00:30:14,083 --> 00:30:16,665
and is now designated
Hurricane Mabeline.

400
00:30:16,750 --> 00:30:18,457
Stay tuned for
further information.

401
00:30:23,833 --> 00:30:28,374
How can we help her?
She's got so many problems.

402
00:30:29,083 --> 00:30:30,874
It's getting worse.

403
00:30:32,541 --> 00:30:34,165
Whose fault is it?

404
00:30:34,250 --> 00:30:35,374
CAPTAIN SHARP:
I don't know.

405
00:30:36,125 --> 00:30:38,874
But just for the record,
95% of all runaways

406
00:30:38,958 --> 00:30:40,832
return home within
the first six hours.

407
00:30:41,416 --> 00:30:44,415
That doesn't do you
any good right now. It's just a statistic.

408
00:30:44,833 --> 00:30:47,290
But in all likelihood,
Suzy's probably hiding in the closet

409
00:30:47,375 --> 00:30:49,665
at her best friend's house
playing Chinese checkers

410
00:30:49,750 --> 00:30:52,082
at this very moment,
as we speak.

411
00:30:52,166 --> 00:30:54,374
She doesn't have any friends.

412
00:30:55,875 --> 00:30:57,249
How's Laura?

413
00:31:00,458 --> 00:31:01,832
"How's Laura?"

414
00:31:01,916 --> 00:31:03,457
Mrs. Bishop, I mean.

415
00:31:03,541 --> 00:31:06,124
I don't understand.

416
00:31:06,208 --> 00:31:07,582
Is she upset?

417
00:31:12,416 --> 00:31:14,624
(INDISTINCT CHATTER
OVER RADIO)

418
00:31:14,708 --> 00:31:16,582
(WESTERN MUSIC PLAYING)

419
00:31:22,000 --> 00:31:23,374
There's a porcupine.

420
00:31:30,916 --> 00:31:32,374
(MUSIC STOPS)

421
00:31:32,875 --> 00:31:37,457
She has a pen pal!
It's very intimate. They planned this together.

422
00:31:38,500 --> 00:31:41,749
Sam Shakusky.
That's my escaped Khaki Scout.

423
00:31:41,833 --> 00:31:42,915
His family died.

424
00:31:43,000 --> 00:31:44,999
Holy Christ,
what am I looking at?

425
00:31:45,083 --> 00:31:48,415
He does watercolors.
Mostly landscapes, but a few nudes.

426
00:31:48,500 --> 00:31:49,540
She sit for this?

427
00:31:49,625 --> 00:31:50,665
What's he say?

428
00:31:53,250 --> 00:31:55,457
Dear Suzy,
you have a superb voice.

429
00:31:55,541 --> 00:31:57,832
You were my favorite animal
in the program, by far.

430
00:31:57,916 --> 00:31:59,249
Please find enclosed...

431
00:31:59,333 --> 00:32:00,999
Dear Sam,
thank you very much.

432
00:32:01,083 --> 00:32:03,832
I got replaced as the raven
because I yelled at Mrs. Lynn.

433
00:32:03,916 --> 00:32:05,665
After that,
I was only a blue jay, but...

434
00:32:05,750 --> 00:32:08,582
Dear Suzy, I'm sorry
that your brothers are so selfish.

435
00:32:08,666 --> 00:32:10,040
Maybe they will
grow out of it.

436
00:32:10,125 --> 00:32:12,624
Sometimes people do things
without knowing the reasons for...

437
00:32:12,708 --> 00:32:14,457
Dear Sam, you are
an excellent painter,

438
00:32:14,541 --> 00:32:16,249
especially trees
and telephone poles.

439
00:32:16,333 --> 00:32:19,415
Is the girl in the water supposed to be
me? My favorite color is...

440
00:32:19,500 --> 00:32:23,207
Dear Suzy, I accidentally built a
fire while I was sleepwalking.

441
00:32:23,291 --> 00:32:26,415
I have no memory of this,
but my foster parents think I am lying.

442
00:32:26,500 --> 00:32:27,540
Unfortunately, it is...

443
00:32:27,625 --> 00:32:29,624
Dear Sam,
I am in trouble again

444
00:32:29,708 --> 00:32:31,207
because I threw a rock
through the window.

445
00:32:31,291 --> 00:32:33,707
My mother still has
glass in her hair. Also...

446
00:32:33,791 --> 00:32:36,290
Dear Suzy, I have been
trying very hard to make friends,

447
00:32:36,375 --> 00:32:38,832
but I feel people do
not like my personality.

448
00:32:38,916 --> 00:32:40,749
In fact, I can understand
why they might not...

449
00:32:40,833 --> 00:32:42,749
Dear Sam,
now I am getting suspended

450
00:32:42,833 --> 00:32:44,332
because I got in
a fight with Molly.

451
00:32:44,416 --> 00:32:47,415
She says I go berserk.
Our principal is against me. Why do some...

452
00:32:47,500 --> 00:32:49,832
Dear Suzy, I know your parents
hurt your feelings,

453
00:32:49,916 --> 00:32:52,915
but they still love you.
That is more important. If they...

454
00:32:53,000 --> 00:32:54,665
Dear Sam,
I do think you should

455
00:32:54,750 --> 00:32:55,915
think of their
faces every day,

456
00:32:56,000 --> 00:32:57,457
even if it makes you sad.

457
00:32:57,541 --> 00:32:58,999
It is too bad they
did not leave you

458
00:32:59,083 --> 00:33:00,999
more pictures of themselves.
Can you...

459
00:33:01,083 --> 00:33:02,999
Dear Suzy, here is my plan.

460
00:33:03,083 --> 00:33:05,082
Dear Sam, my answer is yes.

461
00:33:05,166 --> 00:33:06,582
Dear Suzy, when?

462
00:33:06,666 --> 00:33:08,249
Dear Sam, where?

463
00:33:08,333 --> 00:33:11,832
Dear Suzy,
walk 400 yards due north from your house

464
00:33:11,916 --> 00:33:14,457
to the dirt path
which has not got any name on it.

465
00:33:14,541 --> 00:33:18,415
Turn right and follow to the
end. I will meet you in the meadow.

466
00:33:26,208 --> 00:33:28,499
Gee whiz, what do you
suppose happened to him?

467
00:33:28,583 --> 00:33:31,999
I'm not sure.
I think he went searching in the dark.

468
00:33:32,083 --> 00:33:35,040
She stole the batteries
out of my flashlight.

469
00:33:35,125 --> 00:33:37,665
Stole the batteries
out of the flashlight...

470
00:33:39,833 --> 00:33:41,082
I think he's onto us.

471
00:33:41,166 --> 00:33:42,374
Of course he is.

472
00:33:42,458 --> 00:33:42,957
Of course he is?

473
00:33:43,125 --> 00:33:43,624
(FLY BUZZING)

474
00:33:43,708 --> 00:33:44,790
Of course he is.

475
00:33:46,583 --> 00:33:48,832
Then why aren't we
worried about that?

476
00:33:48,916 --> 00:33:50,540
I am.

477
00:33:50,625 --> 00:33:52,249
Well, I didn't know.

478
00:33:52,333 --> 00:33:55,707
Or, anyway,
I thought maybe I was wrong.

479
00:33:55,791 --> 00:33:56,832
Did you hit him?

480
00:33:56,916 --> 00:33:58,040
No. He fell in a ditch.

481
00:33:58,125 --> 00:34:02,749
Hey! Cat food!
I think it's a clue.

482
00:34:07,208 --> 00:34:08,582
That's her.

483
00:34:10,250 --> 00:34:11,915
Where's he going?

484
00:34:12,708 --> 00:34:14,165
I don't know.

485
00:34:15,708 --> 00:34:17,374
All right,
we know they're together.

486
00:34:17,458 --> 00:34:19,665
We know they're within
a certain radius of this spot.

487
00:34:19,750 --> 00:34:21,999
I'm declaring a case
with the county right now.

488
00:34:22,083 --> 00:34:25,582
Until help arrives,
I'm deputizing the little guy, the skinny one,

489
00:34:25,666 --> 00:34:27,082
and the boy with
the patch on his eye

490
00:34:27,166 --> 00:34:28,499
to come with me in
the station wagon.

491
00:34:28,583 --> 00:34:31,665
Randy, you drop in and head up
river with the rest of your troops,

492
00:34:31,750 --> 00:34:32,999
split up on foot.

493
00:34:33,083 --> 00:34:35,165
Becky, call Jed,
tell him to circle over

494
00:34:35,250 --> 00:34:37,707
this end of the island
and fly low.

495
00:34:50,166 --> 00:34:51,249
SAM: Is it them?

496
00:34:51,333 --> 00:34:52,374
SUZY: Yeah, yeah.

497
00:34:53,541 --> 00:34:54,832
They found the campfire.

498
00:34:54,916 --> 00:34:59,749
Rats! I should have put
more pine needles on it. Let's go.

499
00:35:06,083 --> 00:35:07,332
SAM: Be careful.

500
00:35:38,458 --> 00:35:40,082
What do you creeps want?

501
00:35:40,875 --> 00:35:42,290
We're looking for you.

502
00:35:43,250 --> 00:35:44,374
Why?

503
00:35:44,958 --> 00:35:46,332
Well, because
you're a fugitive.

504
00:35:46,416 --> 00:35:48,665
No, I'm not.
I quit the Khaki Scouts.

505
00:35:48,750 --> 00:35:51,165
Well, it doesn't matter
anyway. You don't have that authority.

506
00:35:51,250 --> 00:35:52,540
We've been deputized.

507
00:35:52,625 --> 00:35:55,874
Now, you're going to come
along peacefully or not?

508
00:35:59,041 --> 00:36:00,332
Listen to some reason.

509
00:36:00,416 --> 00:36:02,499
I don't like you.
You don't like me.

510
00:36:02,583 --> 00:36:05,290
So, why don't you
just let us disappear?

511
00:36:06,250 --> 00:36:09,165
Well, it's tempting,
but we can't allow it.

512
00:36:10,291 --> 00:36:11,582
You know,
you shouldn't be friends with him.

513
00:36:12,416 --> 00:36:13,457
Why not?

514
00:36:14,166 --> 00:36:15,332
Because he's crazy.

515
00:36:16,583 --> 00:36:18,249
Maybe you just
don't know him.

516
00:36:19,625 --> 00:36:21,499
Actually, we know him
a lot better than you.

517
00:36:21,583 --> 00:36:23,499
He's emotionally disturbed
because his family died.

518
00:36:23,583 --> 00:36:25,290
Nickleby, tie him up.

519
00:36:28,791 --> 00:36:34,207
(SLOWLY)
Do not cross this stick.

520
00:36:42,041 --> 00:36:43,540
You're doomed, Shakusky.

521
00:36:49,666 --> 00:36:51,415
(SCREAMS)

522
00:37:06,416 --> 00:37:08,499
(AGONIZED SCREAMS)

523
00:37:20,333 --> 00:37:22,665
Molly's right,
I do go berserk.

524
00:37:25,000 --> 00:37:26,624
It was him or us.

525
00:37:31,166 --> 00:37:32,332
Oh, no.

526
00:37:37,166 --> 00:37:39,332
She stabbed
Redford in the back with lefty scissors.

527
00:37:39,416 --> 00:37:41,082
JED: (OVER RADIO)
Repeat that, please? Over.

528
00:37:41,166 --> 00:37:44,332
Puncture wound, lower lumbar.
Make room for a stretcher in the cockpit.

529
00:37:44,750 --> 00:37:45,957
You're going to be okay.

530
00:37:46,041 --> 00:37:48,999
Thank goodness she
missed the artery. Here, bite on this.

531
00:37:49,083 --> 00:37:50,915
I tried to chop him,
but he dodged my tomahawk.

532
00:37:51,000 --> 00:37:52,499
He's got
excellent marksmanship.

533
00:37:52,583 --> 00:37:53,790
Shot Deluca in both arms.

534
00:37:53,875 --> 00:37:56,165
I guess we're going to miss
the Hullabaloo after all.

535
00:37:56,250 --> 00:37:57,582
Where's Snoopy?

536
00:37:58,875 --> 00:38:00,874
Those sons of bitches.

537
00:38:00,958 --> 00:38:03,540
They got him right
through the neck.

538
00:38:05,541 --> 00:38:07,207
Was he a good dog?

539
00:38:08,708 --> 00:38:12,915
Who's to say.
But he didn't deserve to die.

540
00:38:29,041 --> 00:38:30,165
What happened?
Who is that?

541
00:38:30,250 --> 00:38:31,332
Clear the dock, Edgar!

542
00:38:31,416 --> 00:38:32,999
-Why is he bleeding?
-Is Suzy with you?

543
00:38:33,083 --> 00:38:34,790
No, she's in
the woods with Shakusky.

544
00:38:34,875 --> 00:38:35,915
JED: Where am I going?

545
00:38:36,000 --> 00:38:38,915
The infirmary at Fort Lebanon.
We'll be right behind you. You got it?

546
00:38:39,000 --> 00:38:40,124
Yup.

547
00:38:40,208 --> 00:38:41,499
Warm up the motor,
I'll be right back.

548
00:38:41,583 --> 00:38:42,874
WALT: Hold it right there!

549
00:38:43,875 --> 00:38:45,040
You're not
leaving this island.

550
00:38:45,125 --> 00:38:47,999
Our daughter has been
abducted by one of these beige lunatics.

551
00:38:48,083 --> 00:38:50,457
Walt, it's very clear.

552
00:38:50,541 --> 00:38:52,499
The two of them
conspired in this together.

553
00:38:52,583 --> 00:38:53,915
Don't worry,
Mr. Bishop. She'll be safe.

554
00:38:54,000 --> 00:38:55,290
Sam's got excellent
wilderness skills.

555
00:38:56,416 --> 00:38:58,415
(SHOUTS) Why can't you
control your Scouts?

556
00:39:00,291 --> 00:39:01,540
(STAMMERS)
Well, I'm trying.

557
00:39:04,541 --> 00:39:05,665
Whoa, whoa. Hey.

558
00:39:05,750 --> 00:39:06,832
LAURA: Stop it! Stop it!

559
00:39:06,916 --> 00:39:08,499
-Stop it!
-Stop it.

560
00:39:08,583 --> 00:39:13,249
I do blame him.
But I also blame myself and both of you.

561
00:39:13,333 --> 00:39:17,832
With all due respect,
you can't let your children stab people.

562
00:39:17,916 --> 00:39:19,457
What are you talking about?

563
00:39:19,541 --> 00:39:21,165
She's violent,
Mrs. Bishop, it's assault.

564
00:39:24,833 --> 00:39:26,374
-Are you a lawyer?
-No, I'm not a lawyer.

565
00:39:26,458 --> 00:39:27,582
Well, we are!

566
00:39:27,666 --> 00:39:28,749
Take your hands
off my wife!

567
00:39:28,833 --> 00:39:29,582
Take them off!

568
00:39:29,750 --> 00:39:30,540
(ALL CLAMORING)

569
00:39:30,625 --> 00:39:34,415
NARRATOR: Excuse me.
Excuse me, Captain Sharp!

570
00:39:38,500 --> 00:39:40,374
As some of you know,
I taught Sam

571
00:39:40,458 --> 00:39:42,749
for the cartography
accomplishment button.

572
00:39:42,833 --> 00:39:45,165
He's a smart boy
and he expressed a keen interest

573
00:39:45,250 --> 00:39:47,790
in the history of the island's
indigenous peoples.

574
00:39:48,333 --> 00:39:51,332
In particular,
I recall his fascination with the idea

575
00:39:51,416 --> 00:39:55,707
of retracing the original
path of the old Chickchaw harvest migration.

576
00:39:59,916 --> 00:40:03,915
What I'm getting at is this.
I think I know where they're going.

577
00:40:10,250 --> 00:40:11,874
MAN: (OVER RECORD PLAYER)
Onto the birdhouse,

578
00:40:11,958 --> 00:40:14,040
where every kind
of bird imaginable

579
00:40:14,125 --> 00:40:16,207
is whirling
and wheeling around.

580
00:40:22,208 --> 00:40:24,707
This is our land!

581
00:40:24,791 --> 00:40:26,415
Yes, it is!

582
00:40:27,541 --> 00:40:30,707
Whoo!

583
00:40:30,791 --> 00:40:31,832
SAM: Run!

584
00:40:49,708 --> 00:40:50,790
Let's jump!

585
00:41:14,791 --> 00:41:15,874
On three!

586
00:41:15,958 --> 00:41:16,999
One, two, three!

587
00:41:17,541 --> 00:41:18,790
(SCREAMS)

588
00:41:23,791 --> 00:41:27,124
(MAN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY
ON RECORD PLAYER)

589
00:41:29,250 --> 00:41:32,540
Any of you who have ever
had to sweat through piano exercises

590
00:41:32,625 --> 00:41:34,790
will sympathize with these...

591
00:41:44,125 --> 00:41:45,999
I like it here,
but I don't like the name.

592
00:41:47,291 --> 00:41:48,499
Me, neither.

593
00:41:48,583 --> 00:41:52,415
"Mile 3.25 Tidal Inlet."
It's got no ring to it.

594
00:41:53,125 --> 00:41:55,415
Let's change it.
What should it be?

595
00:41:56,458 --> 00:41:57,374
Let me think
for a minute.

596
00:41:57,541 --> 00:41:58,499
(MEOWS)

597
00:42:08,583 --> 00:42:10,540
SAM: I made you some jewelry.

598
00:42:15,041 --> 00:42:16,624
Are your ears pierced?

599
00:42:16,916 --> 00:42:18,665
(GASPING)

600
00:42:26,708 --> 00:42:27,915
It's pretty.

601
00:42:29,625 --> 00:42:31,207
Do the other one.

602
00:42:39,333 --> 00:42:41,749
Why do you
always use binoculars?

603
00:42:44,750 --> 00:42:48,082
It helps me see things
closer, even if they're not very far away.

604
00:42:48,833 --> 00:42:50,999
I pretend it's
my magic power.

605
00:42:51,333 --> 00:42:52,374
Hmm.

606
00:42:52,458 --> 00:42:54,374
That sounds like poetry.

607
00:42:54,458 --> 00:42:56,415
Poems don't always
have to rhyme, you know.

608
00:42:56,500 --> 00:42:59,124
They're just
supposed to be creative.

609
00:43:02,291 --> 00:43:05,957
So, what do you want to be
when you grow up?

610
00:43:06,375 --> 00:43:09,915
I don't know.
I want to go on adventures, I think.

611
00:43:10,000 --> 00:43:12,832
Not get stuck in one place.
How about you?

612
00:43:15,125 --> 00:43:18,582
Go on adventures, too.
Not get stuck, too.

613
00:43:18,666 --> 00:43:21,457
Anyway, we can't
predict the exact future.

614
00:43:22,375 --> 00:43:23,415
That's true.

615
00:43:26,041 --> 00:43:28,999
It's possible I may
wet the bed, by the way. Later, I mean.

616
00:43:30,291 --> 00:43:31,332
Okay.

617
00:43:32,041 --> 00:43:34,165
I wish I didn't
have to mention it, but just in case.

618
00:43:34,250 --> 00:43:35,749
I don't want to
make you be offended.

619
00:43:37,291 --> 00:43:38,874
Of course I won't.

620
00:43:40,458 --> 00:43:42,165
What's that one for?

621
00:43:42,250 --> 00:43:43,624
-This?
-Yeah.

622
00:43:45,125 --> 00:43:46,499
It's not
an accomplishment button.

623
00:43:46,583 --> 00:43:48,457
I inherited it
from my mother.

624
00:43:49,083 --> 00:43:52,332
It's not actually meant for a male to
wear, but I don't give a damn.

625
00:43:54,625 --> 00:43:56,499
Are your foster parents
still mad at you,

626
00:43:56,583 --> 00:43:58,457
for getting in
trouble so much?

627
00:43:58,833 --> 00:44:00,874
I don't think so.

628
00:44:00,958 --> 00:44:02,957
We're starting to get to
know each other better.

629
00:44:03,041 --> 00:44:05,040
I feel I'm in
a real family now.

630
00:44:05,125 --> 00:44:07,040
Not like yours,
but similar to one.

631
00:44:08,333 --> 00:44:10,665
I always wished
I was an orphan.

632
00:44:10,750 --> 00:44:12,915
Most of my
favorite characters are.

633
00:44:13,000 --> 00:44:14,957
I think your lives
are more special.

634
00:44:18,541 --> 00:44:20,957
I love you, but you don't know
what you're talking about.

635
00:44:23,583 --> 00:44:25,082
I love you, too.

636
00:44:28,583 --> 00:44:30,999
(UPBEAT INSTRUMENTAL
MUSIC PLAYING)

637
00:45:26,958 --> 00:45:28,999
-I've got sand in my mouth.
-Oh.

638
00:45:30,583 --> 00:45:32,207
Uh... Can you French kiss?

639
00:45:32,916 --> 00:45:35,374
I think so.
Is there any secret to it?

640
00:45:35,458 --> 00:45:37,540
The tongues touch each other.

641
00:45:37,625 --> 00:45:39,332
Okay, let's try it.

642
00:45:51,875 --> 00:45:53,249
It feels hard.

643
00:45:54,125 --> 00:45:55,165
Do you mind?

644
00:45:55,250 --> 00:45:56,290
I like it.

645
00:45:59,125 --> 00:46:00,415
Tilt your head sideways.

646
00:46:08,583 --> 00:46:10,290
You can touch my chest.

647
00:46:12,625 --> 00:46:15,207
I... I think they're
going to grow more.

648
00:46:24,166 --> 00:46:26,374
SUZY: "The flashlight's
beam drew a moon through the black

649
00:46:26,458 --> 00:46:29,082
"across the attic
and settled on a gap in the baseboard.

650
00:46:29,166 --> 00:46:31,790
"A mouse hole,
no bigger than a pocket watch.

651
00:46:32,125 --> 00:46:33,749
"Eric crouched
on his flat feet

652
00:46:33,833 --> 00:46:35,915
"and placed his hand in
front of the tiny opening.

653
00:46:36,000 --> 00:46:37,249
"'It's windy,' he said.

654
00:46:37,333 --> 00:46:39,665
"'Like someone in there's
blowing on my fingers.'

655
00:46:39,750 --> 00:46:41,957
"Christy rolled her
eyes and sighed a sigh.

656
00:46:42,041 --> 00:46:43,707
"'He's right again,'
she thought.

657
00:46:43,791 --> 00:46:45,457
"'Little brothers
drive people crazy."'

658
00:46:51,625 --> 00:46:53,124
I'm listening. Read on.

659
00:46:55,291 --> 00:46:56,582
Part two.

660
00:47:05,541 --> 00:47:07,749
(AIRPLANE PASSING OVERHEAD)

661
00:47:15,166 --> 00:47:16,790
(BOAT ENGINE REVVING)

662
00:47:27,416 --> 00:47:28,457
WALT: No!

663
00:47:50,833 --> 00:47:52,082
(GRUNTS)

664
00:48:08,916 --> 00:48:11,082
HERBERT: Dear Sam, it saddens
me to write this letter,

665
00:48:11,166 --> 00:48:13,165
but Mrs. Billingsley
and I have decided

666
00:48:13,250 --> 00:48:15,249
we cannot permit you
to return to our home.

667
00:48:15,333 --> 00:48:19,040
I know you mean well.
Do trust me, this is for the best.

668
00:48:19,125 --> 00:48:21,374
Godspeed,
Herbert Billingsley.

669
00:48:33,125 --> 00:48:37,624
Be advised, the two of you will
never see each other again.

670
00:48:37,708 --> 00:48:41,582
Those were your last words.
Do you understand?

671
00:48:42,083 --> 00:48:43,624
I'd be careful
if I were you.

672
00:48:43,708 --> 00:48:46,040
One of these days,
somebody's going to get pushed too far,

673
00:48:46,125 --> 00:48:47,874
and who knows what
they're capable of.

674
00:48:48,458 --> 00:48:49,790
Is that a threat?

675
00:48:50,291 --> 00:48:51,332
It's a warning.

676
00:48:51,416 --> 00:48:53,332
You're a traitor
to our family.

677
00:48:53,416 --> 00:48:55,124
Good. I want to be.

678
00:49:00,708 --> 00:49:02,624
(DOOR OPENING)

679
00:49:03,125 --> 00:49:04,582
(DOOR CLOSES)

680
00:49:12,708 --> 00:49:17,374
I'm sorry about this.
I didn't know your situation.

681
00:49:17,458 --> 00:49:19,499
It wasn't in the register.

682
00:49:20,583 --> 00:49:22,749
How'd you lose your parents?

683
00:49:23,958 --> 00:49:26,874
Never mind, I don't
need to ask about that.

684
00:49:30,541 --> 00:49:35,457
I wish we had time
to do an inspection back there. On the beach.

685
00:49:36,500 --> 00:49:39,665
I would have given
you a commendable.

686
00:49:39,750 --> 00:49:41,874
That was one of the
best pitched campsites I've ever seen.

687
00:49:41,958 --> 00:49:43,082
Honestly.

688
00:49:43,166 --> 00:49:44,499
(MEEKLY) Thank you.

689
00:49:47,666 --> 00:49:50,124
You don't want to be
a Khaki Scout anymore?

690
00:49:59,500 --> 00:50:02,165
(FOGHORN BLOWS)

691
00:50:02,958 --> 00:50:03,999
JUDY: Hello, Becky?

692
00:50:04,083 --> 00:50:07,332
Judy, I have your
person-to-person from New Penzance.

693
00:50:07,416 --> 00:50:08,457
Go ahead, New Penzance.

694
00:50:09,083 --> 00:50:10,582
Hello, this is
Captain Sharp.

695
00:50:10,666 --> 00:50:13,040
Hello, Captain Sharp.
This is Social Services.

696
00:50:13,125 --> 00:50:15,707
I'm calling in
reference to Sam Shakusky, ward of the state.

697
00:50:15,791 --> 00:50:16,957
I understand he's
in your custody.

698
00:50:17,041 --> 00:50:18,165
That's correct.

699
00:50:18,250 --> 00:50:20,082
What's his condition?
Has he suffered

700
00:50:20,166 --> 00:50:22,415
any injury or
trauma of any kind?

701
00:50:22,500 --> 00:50:24,249
-He's fine.
-Very good.

702
00:50:24,333 --> 00:50:25,665
How do I get to you?

703
00:50:25,750 --> 00:50:27,290
The fastest way
would be sea plane.

704
00:50:27,416 --> 00:50:28,957
Jed can bring you
in with the mail.

705
00:50:29,041 --> 00:50:30,957
I'll come tomorrow morning,
if that's acceptable to you.

706
00:50:31,041 --> 00:50:32,832
Is someone able to
provide reasonable care

707
00:50:32,916 --> 00:50:34,540
and nourishment for
the boy until that time?

708
00:50:35,166 --> 00:50:36,249
Uh-huh.

709
00:50:36,750 --> 00:50:37,790
Is that a yes?

710
00:50:38,166 --> 00:50:39,249
Uh-huh.

711
00:50:41,000 --> 00:50:43,832
Very good, I'll contact you
again before the end of the day.

712
00:50:43,916 --> 00:50:44,999
Wait a second.

713
00:50:45,083 --> 00:50:46,290
Yes?

714
00:50:46,375 --> 00:50:47,540
Social Services?

715
00:50:47,625 --> 00:50:48,832
Captain Sharp?

716
00:50:49,958 --> 00:50:51,790
What's going to
happen to him?

717
00:50:54,250 --> 00:50:57,582
Well, normally,
we try to place him in another foster home,

718
00:50:57,666 --> 00:50:59,790
but that option's no
longer available to us,

719
00:50:59,875 --> 00:51:02,082
in my opinion,
due to his case history.

720
00:51:02,166 --> 00:51:04,415
Which means he'll go
to Juvenile Refuge.

721
00:51:04,833 --> 00:51:07,332
Wait. What does that mean?
Is that an orphanage?

722
00:51:08,000 --> 00:51:09,040
Who's speaking?

723
00:51:09,458 --> 00:51:11,207
This is Scout Master
Randy Ward.

724
00:51:13,666 --> 00:51:15,249
Right, an orphanage.

725
00:51:19,291 --> 00:51:22,165
But the first step is
the admissions panel

726
00:51:22,250 --> 00:51:23,915
requires
a psychological evaluation

727
00:51:24,000 --> 00:51:26,415
to determine
whether or not the boy

728
00:51:26,500 --> 00:51:28,457
is a candidate for
institutional treatment

729
00:51:28,541 --> 00:51:31,082
or electroshock therapy.

730
00:51:31,166 --> 00:51:33,165
Excuse me.
Shock therapy?

731
00:51:33,250 --> 00:51:35,415
Why would that
be called for? He's not violent.

732
00:51:35,916 --> 00:51:38,415
The report describes
an assault with scissors.

733
00:51:38,500 --> 00:51:39,665
That was the girl.

734
00:51:39,750 --> 00:51:40,915
That was the girl
that did that.

735
00:51:41,458 --> 00:51:46,499
Well, maybe she needs help,
too, but that's not our job. Okay?

736
00:51:50,291 --> 00:51:51,332
Okay.

737
00:52:27,791 --> 00:52:29,374
I'll be out back.

738
00:52:30,750 --> 00:52:33,415
I'm going to find
a tree to chop down.

739
00:52:38,333 --> 00:52:41,457
I do know what
you're feeling, Suzy-bean.

740
00:52:41,541 --> 00:52:45,499
I've had moments
myself where I say, "What am I doing here?

741
00:52:45,583 --> 00:52:47,040
"Who made this decision?

742
00:52:47,875 --> 00:52:51,040
"How could I allow myself
to do something so stupid?

743
00:52:51,125 --> 00:52:53,457
"And why is it
still happening?"

744
00:52:55,291 --> 00:52:57,124
We women are
more emotional...

745
00:52:57,208 --> 00:52:58,624
I hate you.

746
00:52:59,666 --> 00:53:00,957
Don't say "hate."

747
00:53:01,041 --> 00:53:02,499
Why not? I mean it.

748
00:53:03,375 --> 00:53:06,540
You think you mean it,
in this moment. You're trying to hurt me.

749
00:53:06,625 --> 00:53:07,832
Exactly.

750
00:53:09,291 --> 00:53:12,540
I know what you do
with that sad, dumb policeman.

751
00:53:19,375 --> 00:53:20,915
He's not dumb.

752
00:53:21,916 --> 00:53:24,165
But I guess
he is kind of sad.

753
00:53:26,041 --> 00:53:27,540
Anyway,
we shouldn't discuss that.

754
00:53:27,625 --> 00:53:29,540
It's not appropriate
for me to even acknowledge

755
00:53:29,625 --> 00:53:32,124
what I already just said.

756
00:53:40,666 --> 00:53:41,874
(SIGHS)

757
00:53:41,958 --> 00:53:43,290
Poor Suzy.

758
00:53:45,375 --> 00:53:47,832
Why is everything
so hard for you?

759
00:53:49,500 --> 00:53:54,499
We're in love. We just want to be
together. What's wrong with that?

760
00:53:59,583 --> 00:54:04,540
Oh, my God! How are we going to
get these fish hooks out?

761
00:54:06,500 --> 00:54:07,749
(SOFT MUSIC PLAYING)

762
00:54:07,833 --> 00:54:11,040
SAM: I admit we knew
we'd get in trouble. That part's true.

763
00:54:11,500 --> 00:54:15,082
We knew people would be
worried, and we still ran away, anyway.

764
00:54:15,166 --> 00:54:18,457
But something also happened,
which we didn't do on purpose.

765
00:54:18,541 --> 00:54:22,707
When we first met each other,
something happened to us.

766
00:54:24,291 --> 00:54:25,665
That's very eloquent.

767
00:54:26,291 --> 00:54:28,582
I can't argue against
anything you're saying.

768
00:54:29,250 --> 00:54:32,415
But then again,
I don't have to, 'cause you're 12 years old.

769
00:54:34,708 --> 00:54:37,624
Look, let's face it.

770
00:54:39,250 --> 00:54:42,832
You're probably a much more
intelligent person than I am.

771
00:54:43,708 --> 00:54:45,874
In fact,
I guarantee it.

772
00:54:45,958 --> 00:54:47,790
But even smart kids
stick their finger

773
00:54:47,875 --> 00:54:49,457
in electrical
sockets sometimes.

774
00:54:51,416 --> 00:54:53,832
It takes time to
figure things out.

775
00:54:54,541 --> 00:54:58,082
It's been proven by history.
All mankind makes mistakes.

776
00:55:00,083 --> 00:55:01,415
It's our job to
try to protect you

777
00:55:01,500 --> 00:55:04,707
from making the
dangerous ones, if we can.

778
00:55:04,791 --> 00:55:06,457
You want a slug?

779
00:55:16,791 --> 00:55:18,540
What's your rush?

780
00:55:18,625 --> 00:55:22,207
You've got your whole life
in front of yourself.

781
00:55:22,291 --> 00:55:23,665
Ahead of you, I mean.

782
00:55:24,000 --> 00:55:26,540
Maybe so.
Anyway, you're a bachelor.

783
00:55:28,000 --> 00:55:29,040
So are you.

784
00:55:29,125 --> 00:55:30,165
That's true.

785
00:55:32,958 --> 00:55:34,915
Did you love someone ever?

786
00:55:37,083 --> 00:55:38,290
Yes, I did.

787
00:55:38,375 --> 00:55:39,540
What happened?

788
00:55:41,458 --> 00:55:43,124
She didn't love me back.

789
00:55:43,625 --> 00:55:44,665
Ah.

790
00:55:47,666 --> 00:55:50,665
I'm sorry for your loss.

791
00:55:50,750 --> 00:55:52,540
Anyway, that's what
you're supposed to say.

792
00:56:17,625 --> 00:56:19,374
Scout Master's log.
September 4th.

793
00:56:35,625 --> 00:56:37,290
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

794
00:56:38,625 --> 00:56:40,207
I heard he's going
to reform school.

795
00:56:40,291 --> 00:56:42,165
I heard that they're
going to take out a piece of his brain,

796
00:56:42,250 --> 00:56:43,749
send him to
an insane asylum.

797
00:56:43,833 --> 00:56:44,957
I like his girl.

798
00:56:45,041 --> 00:56:46,124
She's too scruffy for me.

799
00:56:46,208 --> 00:56:47,415
Supposedly,
they got to third base.

800
00:56:47,500 --> 00:56:48,999
That's not true.
He just felt her up.

801
00:56:49,083 --> 00:56:50,124
Over shirt or under shirt?

802
00:56:52,041 --> 00:56:53,290
Damn us.

803
00:56:57,125 --> 00:56:59,124
It's none of our business.

804
00:57:04,333 --> 00:57:08,332
This troop has been
very shabby to Field Mate Sam Shakusky.

805
00:57:08,416 --> 00:57:11,290
In fact, we've been
a bunch of mean jerks.

806
00:57:14,875 --> 00:57:16,665
Why's he so unpopular?

807
00:57:17,500 --> 00:57:20,040
I admit, supposedly,
he's emotionally disturbed,

808
00:57:20,125 --> 00:57:24,624
but he's also
a disadvantaged orphan. How would you feel?

809
00:57:24,708 --> 00:57:25,790
Nickleby?

810
00:57:26,625 --> 00:57:27,665
Deluca?

811
00:57:28,375 --> 00:57:29,415
Lazy-Eye?

812
00:57:29,916 --> 00:57:30,957
Gadge?

813
00:57:31,625 --> 00:57:34,707
He's a fellow Khaki Scout,
and he needs our help.

814
00:57:34,791 --> 00:57:36,540
Are we man enough
to give that

815
00:57:36,625 --> 00:57:39,707
so part of his brain
doesn't get removed out of him?

816
00:57:40,541 --> 00:57:43,249
They were prepared
to die for each other out there.

817
00:57:44,000 --> 00:57:46,790
(ALL MURMURING INDISTINCTLY)

818
00:57:46,875 --> 00:57:50,540
Okay. Okay.
What do you need?

819
00:57:50,625 --> 00:57:52,540
For starters?
Three yards of chicken wire,

820
00:57:52,625 --> 00:57:54,874
some ripped up newspapers,
and a bucket of wheat paste.

821
00:58:22,458 --> 00:58:24,874
In other words, it's over.

822
00:58:24,958 --> 00:58:28,749
I guess so.
For the moment.

823
00:58:28,833 --> 00:58:31,124
Until further notice.

824
00:58:31,208 --> 00:58:32,332
That's right.

825
00:58:32,416 --> 00:58:33,457
I understand.

826
00:58:35,000 --> 00:58:38,249
I have to do better,
for everybody.

827
00:58:38,333 --> 00:58:39,790
Except me.

828
00:58:39,875 --> 00:58:41,290
Except you.

829
00:58:42,416 --> 00:58:46,165
Well, I hope you can.
I think you will.

830
00:58:47,166 --> 00:58:49,457
You're doing
the right thing.

831
00:58:55,166 --> 00:58:56,790
(CAR DOOR CLOSES)

832
00:58:56,875 --> 00:58:58,415
(ENGINE STARTS)

833
00:58:59,666 --> 00:59:01,915
(MELLOW MUSIC
PLAYING ON RADIO)

834
00:59:04,000 --> 00:59:06,624
Who knows what's
going to happen, Duffy?

835
00:59:06,708 --> 00:59:08,457
I'll probably
see you tomorrow.

836
00:59:32,791 --> 00:59:34,165
(SOFT THUD)

837
00:59:44,958 --> 00:59:46,207
(TAPPING)

838
00:59:50,625 --> 00:59:52,207
(WHISPERS)
Get out of my chimney.

839
00:59:52,291 --> 00:59:53,457
Listen to me.

840
00:59:53,541 --> 00:59:56,624
We're here for friendship.
We're going to get you off this island.

841
00:59:56,708 --> 00:59:57,790
No, thanks.

842
00:59:57,875 --> 01:00:00,207
Yes, thanks.
This is an emergency rescue.

843
01:00:00,791 --> 01:00:04,249
It's worthless to me.
There's no point, not without Suzy.

844
01:00:09,958 --> 01:00:11,207
How'd you get here?

845
01:00:11,291 --> 01:00:12,957
They snuck me down
the laundry chute

846
01:00:13,041 --> 01:00:14,915
and left a papier-mch
dummy in my bed.

847
01:00:15,291 --> 01:00:18,290
Hmm... Diversion tactics.
Good thinking.

848
01:00:30,041 --> 01:00:31,540
(SOFT SNORING)

849
01:00:35,708 --> 01:00:36,749
SAM: Where we going?

850
01:00:36,833 --> 01:00:37,874
SKOTAK: Fort Lebanon.

851
01:00:37,958 --> 01:00:41,040
My cousin Ben runs the Supply and
Resources outpost for the Hullabaloo.

852
01:00:41,125 --> 01:00:44,374
He's a Falcon Scout,
Legionnaire. Cousin Ben'll know what to do.

853
01:00:44,458 --> 01:00:45,999
SAM: Can we trust him?

854
01:00:46,083 --> 01:00:47,915
SKOTAK: Normally, I'd say no.

855
01:00:49,708 --> 01:00:51,540
Did you leave
another note for Lionel?

856
01:00:51,625 --> 01:00:53,707
Not this time.
He can't keep his trap shut.

857
01:00:53,791 --> 01:00:55,457
Besides, I'll probably
never see him again.

858
01:00:55,541 --> 01:00:56,582
True.

859
01:01:05,125 --> 01:01:06,415
(BEEPING)

860
01:01:13,750 --> 01:01:16,249
This is the island
of St. Jack Wood,

861
01:01:16,333 --> 01:01:18,040
extending far north
from Land's End

862
01:01:18,125 --> 01:01:21,457
along the deep water channel
that leads to Broken Rock.

863
01:01:25,291 --> 01:01:29,207
A low flood plain
separates the beach from the township above.

864
01:01:29,291 --> 01:01:32,790
A small but
prosperous community.

865
01:01:32,875 --> 01:01:35,457
The barometer reads
28 inches and dropping.

866
01:01:35,541 --> 01:01:40,082
Strong winds, as you can see,
already at 22 knots.

867
01:01:40,166 --> 01:01:41,832
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

868
01:01:43,125 --> 01:01:46,332
The time is now 4:35 a.m.

869
01:02:06,375 --> 01:02:10,874
Did you file the motion
of continuance? Peabody v. Henderson?

870
01:02:10,958 --> 01:02:12,207
WALT: It was sustained.

871
01:02:12,291 --> 01:02:13,540
Good.

872
01:02:15,125 --> 01:02:17,582
Did the judge consider
your application for leniency?

873
01:02:17,666 --> 01:02:18,999
Rogers v. Yentob?

874
01:02:19,083 --> 01:02:20,957
-He granted it.
-Great.

875
01:02:24,583 --> 01:02:26,124
I'm sorry, Walt.

876
01:02:28,541 --> 01:02:31,457
It's not your fault.

877
01:02:33,375 --> 01:02:37,207
Which injuries
are you apologizing for, specifically?

878
01:02:37,291 --> 01:02:39,624
Specifically?

879
01:02:39,708 --> 01:02:42,040
Whichever ones still hurt.

880
01:02:42,958 --> 01:02:45,415
Half of those
were self-inflicted.

881
01:02:51,875 --> 01:02:55,707
I hope the roof flies off,
and I get sucked up into space.

882
01:02:56,416 --> 01:02:58,207
You'll be better
off without me.

883
01:03:00,125 --> 01:03:02,665
Stop feeling
sorry for yourself.

884
01:03:05,958 --> 01:03:07,499
Why?

885
01:03:11,791 --> 01:03:13,957
We're all
they've got, Walt.

886
01:03:21,791 --> 01:03:23,749
That's not enough.

887
01:03:32,291 --> 01:03:34,207
SUZY: "'But I'm not going,'
said Barnaby Jack.

888
01:03:34,291 --> 01:03:35,540
"'I'm running away
tonight for good.

889
01:03:35,625 --> 01:03:37,749
"'And this time I
won't get caught.'

890
01:03:37,833 --> 01:03:40,165
"Annabelle whispered,
'I'm coming with you.'

891
01:03:40,250 --> 01:03:42,040
"Her yellow hair,
now brown at the roots,

892
01:03:42,125 --> 01:03:43,915
"caught up in
the wind and danced.

893
01:03:44,000 --> 01:03:45,582
"Barnaby Jack
took Annabelle's hand

894
01:03:45,666 --> 01:03:48,332
"and pressed something into it
the size of a jellybean.

895
01:03:48,416 --> 01:03:51,415
"'Hide this in your socks,
and be ready at midnight."'

896
01:03:54,250 --> 01:03:55,915
Continue.

897
01:03:56,000 --> 01:03:57,040
Keep going.

898
01:03:57,125 --> 01:03:58,582
-Keep going.
-Go on.

899
01:03:58,666 --> 01:03:59,790
-We're listening.
-That's good.

900
01:04:01,625 --> 01:04:05,457
"He leapt out the window
and landed in the fresh fallen snow."

901
01:04:06,791 --> 01:04:08,124
(CREAKING)

902
01:04:11,000 --> 01:04:13,624
Where's my record player?

903
01:04:19,041 --> 01:04:21,040
(LIONEL SCREAMS)

904
01:04:55,166 --> 01:04:56,957
(MORSE CODE BEEPING)

905
01:05:05,375 --> 01:05:06,624
(BEEPING)

906
01:05:24,000 --> 01:05:25,540
You're not going to
believe this one, sir.

907
01:05:25,625 --> 01:05:29,624
That Scout Master on
New Penzance has now lost his entire troop.

908
01:05:34,291 --> 01:05:36,290
Well, I'll be damned!

909
01:05:36,416 --> 01:05:37,540
Who is this bimbo?

910
01:05:37,625 --> 01:05:38,790
Couldn't say, sir.

911
01:05:46,458 --> 01:05:48,082
(TRUMPET BLOWING)

912
01:05:55,291 --> 01:05:56,790
Be right back.

913
01:06:01,041 --> 01:06:04,832
There's a broken
gumball machine right behind the snack tent.

914
01:06:06,458 --> 01:06:08,040
I don't care how they do it
where you come from.

915
01:06:08,125 --> 01:06:11,040
You want pop? You want candy?
You want a snake bite kit?

916
01:06:11,125 --> 01:06:12,249
Get some money.

917
01:06:12,333 --> 01:06:13,915
Cousin Ben?

918
01:06:14,000 --> 01:06:16,040
Come back in five minutes.

919
01:06:19,541 --> 01:06:20,582
Is this him?

920
01:06:20,666 --> 01:06:22,665
Field Mate Sam Shakusky,
Troop 55, resigned.

921
01:06:22,750 --> 01:06:24,540
He's hot. Almost too hot.
What's in the can?

922
01:06:24,625 --> 01:06:26,040
$76, but it's mostly
in nickels.

923
01:06:26,125 --> 01:06:27,207
Give it to me.

924
01:06:27,291 --> 01:06:28,915
-Your badge in seamanship?
-Yes, sir.

925
01:06:29,000 --> 01:06:31,415
Good. There's a cold water
crabber moored off Broken Rock.

926
01:06:31,500 --> 01:06:32,665
The skipper owes me an IOU.

927
01:06:32,750 --> 01:06:34,915
We'll see if he
can take you on as a claw cracker.

928
01:06:35,000 --> 01:06:36,915
It won't be an easy life,
but it's better than shock therapy.

929
01:06:37,000 --> 01:06:38,207
Thank you, sir.

930
01:06:38,291 --> 01:06:39,999
By the way,
where's the chapel tent?

931
01:06:40,083 --> 01:06:41,290
Back there,
but the padre's home with the mumps.

932
01:06:41,375 --> 01:06:42,540
Why do you ask?

933
01:06:42,625 --> 01:06:44,624
I want to bring my wife.

934
01:06:47,083 --> 01:06:48,499
But we're not married yet.

935
01:06:48,583 --> 01:06:49,707
You his girl?

936
01:06:49,791 --> 01:06:50,832
Yeah.

937
01:06:51,666 --> 01:06:53,707
Technically,
I'm a civil law scrivener.

938
01:06:53,791 --> 01:06:56,415
I'm authorized
to declare births, deaths, and marriages.

939
01:06:56,500 --> 01:06:58,082
You're kind of young.
You got a license?

940
01:06:58,166 --> 01:06:59,457
-No.
-No.

941
01:07:02,125 --> 01:07:03,999
I can't offer you
a legally binding union.

942
01:07:04,083 --> 01:07:05,582
It won't hold up in
the state, the county,

943
01:07:05,666 --> 01:07:07,040
or, frankly,
any courtroom in the world

944
01:07:07,125 --> 01:07:08,540
due to your age,
lack of a license,

945
01:07:08,625 --> 01:07:10,249
and failure to get
parental consent.

946
01:07:10,333 --> 01:07:12,915
But the ritual does
carry a very important

947
01:07:13,000 --> 01:07:14,707
moral weight
within yourselves.

948
01:07:14,791 --> 01:07:17,749
You can't enter
into this lightly. Look into my eyes.

949
01:07:17,833 --> 01:07:19,540
-Do you love each other?
-Yes, we do.

950
01:07:19,625 --> 01:07:20,707
But think about
what I'm saying.

951
01:07:20,791 --> 01:07:21,832
Are you sure
you're ready for this?

952
01:07:21,916 --> 01:07:23,540
-Yes, we are.
-They're not listening to me.

953
01:07:23,625 --> 01:07:25,415
-Let me rephrase it.
-We're in a hurry.

954
01:07:25,500 --> 01:07:26,624
Are you chewing...

955
01:07:26,708 --> 01:07:28,124
Spit out the gum, sister.
In fact, everybody.

956
01:07:28,291 --> 01:07:29,749
(SPITTING)

957
01:07:31,416 --> 01:07:32,665
I don't like
the snappy attitude.

958
01:07:32,750 --> 01:07:35,040
This is the most
important decision you've made in your lives.

959
01:07:35,125 --> 01:07:36,540
Go over by that trampoline
and talk it through

960
01:07:36,625 --> 01:07:39,415
before you give me
another quick answer.

961
01:07:42,166 --> 01:07:43,332
(SIGHS)

962
01:07:48,625 --> 01:07:49,999
(INAUDIBLE)

963
01:07:57,291 --> 01:07:58,374
We're sure.

964
01:07:58,458 --> 01:08:00,457
Okay. Let's do a blood test.

965
01:08:00,541 --> 01:08:02,040
Under the eye of God,

966
01:08:02,125 --> 01:08:04,332
and within the boundaries of
this local jurisdiction,

967
01:08:04,416 --> 01:08:09,207
which we hereby consecrate on this
day, the 5th of September, 1 965.

968
01:08:09,291 --> 01:08:10,374
That's the end
of the short form.

969
01:08:10,458 --> 01:08:12,415
Do any of the witnesses
have objections or remarks?

970
01:08:12,500 --> 01:08:14,874
Usually they don't. Skotak?

971
01:08:14,958 --> 01:08:17,165
Can we loan them the nickels?
I'm worried about their future.

972
01:08:17,250 --> 01:08:19,165
That's my fee.

973
01:08:19,250 --> 01:08:20,415
-What do you think?
-I don't know.

974
01:08:20,500 --> 01:08:23,915
What'd I just say?
That's my fee. I'm keeping the nickels.

975
01:08:32,500 --> 01:08:34,124
Okay, they can have
the tennis ball can.

976
01:08:34,875 --> 01:08:37,540
Sign here,
initial here and here.

977
01:08:38,416 --> 01:08:41,249
Take the carbon,
leave the Bible. Let's go.

978
01:10:10,666 --> 01:10:12,040
Where are they going, again?

979
01:10:12,125 --> 01:10:14,707
He's going to
work on a shrimper, if I understand correctly.

980
01:10:14,791 --> 01:10:16,707
-I wish them well.
-Me, too.

981
01:10:16,791 --> 01:10:18,582
Me, too.

982
01:10:18,666 --> 01:10:20,290
I think they're coming back.

983
01:10:23,291 --> 01:10:25,124
-Be quick, sailor!
-What happened?

984
01:10:25,458 --> 01:10:27,415
She left her
binoculars on a hook in the chapel tent.

985
01:10:28,458 --> 01:10:29,499
Just leave them.

986
01:10:29,583 --> 01:10:31,415
We can't.
It's her magic power!

987
01:10:44,458 --> 01:10:47,249
You killed your dog,
by the way.

988
01:10:47,333 --> 01:10:48,790
-Snoopy?
-Mmm-hmm.

989
01:10:50,208 --> 01:10:51,624
Well, it couldn't be helped.

990
01:10:54,458 --> 01:10:56,124
Why do you
consider me your enemy?

991
01:10:57,791 --> 01:10:58,957
(SCOFFS) Because your
girlfriend stabbed me

992
01:10:59,041 --> 01:11:00,582
in the back with
lefty scissors.

993
01:11:01,458 --> 01:11:02,665
She's my wife now.

994
01:11:04,458 --> 01:11:05,749
Congratulations.

995
01:11:06,125 --> 01:11:09,957
Thank you, but I'm saying before
that, six weeks ago, from day one.

996
01:11:11,125 --> 01:11:12,957
Why don't you like me?

997
01:11:13,791 --> 01:11:16,957
Why should I?
Nobody else does.

998
01:11:22,333 --> 01:11:23,874
(BOTH GRUNTING)

999
01:11:24,291 --> 01:11:25,374
(SCREAMING)

1000
01:11:28,416 --> 01:11:31,040
My God! He's here!
The fugitive! Stop him!

1001
01:11:31,125 --> 01:11:32,707
Stop him!

1002
01:11:34,375 --> 01:11:36,290
(ALARM BLARING)

1003
01:11:36,625 --> 01:11:38,290
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

1004
01:11:58,125 --> 01:11:59,624
(ALL SHOUTING)

1005
01:12:29,458 --> 01:12:31,790
On this spot,
I'll fight no more, forever.

1006
01:12:31,875 --> 01:12:33,999
Come and get me,
you bastards!

1007
01:12:43,708 --> 01:12:45,457
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

1008
01:12:48,291 --> 01:12:49,790
I'm okay.

1009
01:12:53,166 --> 01:12:54,207
Follow me.

1010
01:12:56,875 --> 01:12:58,582
(ALL SHOUTING)

1011
01:13:01,333 --> 01:13:03,082
Company, let's go!

1012
01:13:12,208 --> 01:13:13,874
Captain Sharp,
we've located the missing troop.

1013
01:13:13,958 --> 01:13:16,040
They just fled camp.
We're in pursuit.

1014
01:13:16,125 --> 01:13:17,749
They're accompanied
by a 12-year-old girl

1015
01:13:17,833 --> 01:13:19,374
in knee socks
and Sunday school shoes.

1016
01:13:19,458 --> 01:13:21,540
Stand by,
Commander Pierce.

1017
01:13:22,166 --> 01:13:23,874
Jed, re-route to
St. Jack Wood.

1018
01:13:23,958 --> 01:13:25,915
Tell Social Services
the boy's at Fort Lebanon.

1019
01:13:26,000 --> 01:13:27,040
Roger that.
Will comply.

1020
01:13:27,125 --> 01:13:28,707
Notify the Bishops,
Suzy's there.

1021
01:13:28,791 --> 01:13:29,874
Randy, you monitoring?

1022
01:13:29,958 --> 01:13:32,082
Affirmative.
I'm on my way.

1023
01:13:33,291 --> 01:13:34,332
WALT: Hello?

1024
01:13:34,416 --> 01:13:35,457
Hello, Mr. Bishop?

1025
01:13:35,791 --> 01:13:37,457
Oh, dear God.
Get the boys!

1026
01:13:38,958 --> 01:13:40,624
Let's go! Right now!

1027
01:13:41,125 --> 01:13:42,665
Tower control,
this is Jed.

1028
01:13:42,750 --> 01:13:46,749
Confirm coordinates for new
destination, Alpha two-two-seven-one-fiver.

1029
01:13:46,833 --> 01:13:48,165
Looking pretty soupy up here.

1030
01:13:48,250 --> 01:13:51,124
Wouldn't mind setting down
before the pot boils over.

1031
01:13:51,208 --> 01:13:52,499
Hang on, Social Services.

1032
01:14:12,416 --> 01:14:14,457
MAN: Once again, storm
waters have just breached

1033
01:14:14,541 --> 01:14:16,207
the dam at
Black Beacon Reservoir.

1034
01:14:16,291 --> 01:14:19,457
A flash flood
alert is in effect. Take immediate precautions.

1035
01:14:20,250 --> 01:14:22,040
That's coming our way.

1036
01:14:22,125 --> 01:14:23,790
Did you find them?

1037
01:14:23,875 --> 01:14:26,499
Prepare to mobilize
to higher ground.

1038
01:14:28,833 --> 01:14:31,874
St. Jack's Church
is the designated storm shelter.

1039
01:14:31,958 --> 01:14:34,957
Notify all Scouts to
muster outside my tent, on the double.

1040
01:14:52,041 --> 01:14:53,290
(BLOWING)

1041
01:15:13,041 --> 01:15:15,040
Attention, company!

1042
01:15:15,125 --> 01:15:16,749
Prepare for...

1043
01:15:17,625 --> 01:15:18,957
Who's that?

1044
01:15:29,250 --> 01:15:31,290
You call yourself
a Khaki Scout?

1045
01:15:31,791 --> 01:15:32,832
Sorry, sir?

1046
01:15:32,916 --> 01:15:35,457
Where's your goddamn troop,
you son of a bitch?

1047
01:15:35,541 --> 01:15:36,874
You don't have them?

1048
01:15:36,958 --> 01:15:39,332
They could get
killed out there!

1049
01:15:40,791 --> 01:15:42,540
I'm field stripping
you of your command.

1050
01:15:51,416 --> 01:15:52,874
Attention, company!

1051
01:15:52,958 --> 01:15:55,207
Prepare for
emergency evacuation!

1052
01:15:55,291 --> 01:15:57,624
Sir, do you have
your medicine?

1053
01:15:59,041 --> 01:16:00,832
I'll be right back.

1054
01:16:07,791 --> 01:16:09,457
(DISTANT RUMBLING)

1055
01:16:30,041 --> 01:16:31,499
(ALL EXCLAIM)

1056
01:16:31,583 --> 01:16:32,957
(INAUDIBLE)

1057
01:16:35,291 --> 01:16:37,207
Hold your positions!

1058
01:16:52,125 --> 01:16:53,957
(FIREWORKS EXPLODING)

1059
01:17:08,041 --> 01:17:09,540
Company secretary,
status report.

1060
01:17:09,625 --> 01:17:11,249
All accounted for,
Scout Master!

1061
01:17:11,333 --> 01:17:14,749
Okay, boys,
we're going to make a run for it! Fall in!

1062
01:17:14,833 --> 01:17:17,082
Let's move!

1063
01:17:17,166 --> 01:17:19,374
Come on, follow me!

1064
01:17:19,458 --> 01:17:21,582
(ALL SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)

1065
01:17:31,458 --> 01:17:33,624
(ALL MURMURING INDISTINCTLY)

1066
01:17:38,083 --> 01:17:39,124
(OPERATIC MUSIC PLAYING)

1067
01:17:39,208 --> 01:17:40,624
(DOOR OPENS)

1068
01:17:42,791 --> 01:17:44,124
Who's in charge here?

1069
01:17:44,625 --> 01:17:45,707
Randy, what happened?

1070
01:17:45,791 --> 01:17:46,874
Take the commander off me!

1071
01:17:48,541 --> 01:17:50,540
Suzy?

1072
01:17:50,625 --> 01:17:52,874
Suzy? Sam?

1073
01:17:52,958 --> 01:17:54,040
They ran away again.

1074
01:17:56,833 --> 01:17:58,790
We got to go back out there.
I need volunteers.

1075
01:17:58,875 --> 01:18:01,040
You, and you and you.

1076
01:18:01,125 --> 01:18:02,957
-You?
-Are you all right?

1077
01:18:03,041 --> 01:18:04,290
Of course I am.

1078
01:18:09,458 --> 01:18:10,874
(DOOR OPENS)

1079
01:18:17,000 --> 01:18:18,124
Where's the boy?

1080
01:18:19,041 --> 01:18:20,249
(QUIETLY) We don't know yet.

1081
01:18:20,625 --> 01:18:21,665
That's not acceptable.

1082
01:18:22,416 --> 01:18:24,374
What do you
want me to say, lady?

1083
01:18:24,458 --> 01:18:25,790
Somebody get
Jed a cup of coffee.

1084
01:18:28,000 --> 01:18:29,624
-You're Captain Sharp.
-That's correct.

1085
01:18:29,708 --> 01:18:32,749
I'm Social Services. I remanded the
boy into your personal custody.

1086
01:18:32,833 --> 01:18:34,165
You're responsible
for his safety.

1087
01:18:34,250 --> 01:18:36,665
I'm told that
he's just been struck by lightning.

1088
01:18:36,750 --> 01:18:38,082
That's the first
I've heard of it.

1089
01:18:38,166 --> 01:18:39,207
It's true.

1090
01:18:39,291 --> 01:18:40,582
Scout Master Ward,
I presume.

1091
01:18:40,666 --> 01:18:41,707
Yes, ma'am.

1092
01:18:41,791 --> 01:18:43,165
Your reputation
precedes you.

1093
01:18:43,708 --> 01:18:45,665
You two are
the most appallingly

1094
01:18:45,750 --> 01:18:47,249
incompetent
custodial guardians

1095
01:18:47,333 --> 01:18:49,332
Social Services has
ever had the misfortune

1096
01:18:49,416 --> 01:18:51,790
to encounter in
a 27-year career!

1097
01:18:52,583 --> 01:18:54,165
What do you have to
say for yourselves?

1098
01:18:54,250 --> 01:18:56,749
You can't do this.
They'll eat him alive in there.

1099
01:18:56,833 --> 01:18:57,874
Where?

1100
01:18:57,958 --> 01:18:59,374
(WHISPERS) What's the name
of the place again?

1101
01:18:59,458 --> 01:19:02,374
Juvenile Refuge.

1102
01:19:02,458 --> 01:19:04,082
Sounds like jail.

1103
01:19:04,166 --> 01:19:08,957
Just find the boy,
and deliver him to Social Services.

1104
01:19:09,041 --> 01:19:10,832
Nothing else
is in your power.

1105
01:19:10,916 --> 01:19:12,790
I'm sorry.
Can we get back to the rescue now?

1106
01:19:12,916 --> 01:19:14,540
-Suzy is still out there.
-SOCIAL SERVICES: Who are you?

1107
01:19:14,625 --> 01:19:16,749
Walt and Laura Bishop,
their daughter's the missing girl.

1108
01:19:16,833 --> 01:19:17,874
The parents of the stabber?

1109
01:19:17,958 --> 01:19:20,040
I object to that description.
She was attacked.

1110
01:19:20,125 --> 01:19:21,165
PIERCE: Excuse me?

1111
01:19:21,250 --> 01:19:23,540
I want the details about that.
Where's the Scout she knifed?

1112
01:19:23,625 --> 01:19:24,999
Right here.

1113
01:19:25,083 --> 01:19:27,040
-Field Mate Redford, sir.
-What's his condition?

1114
01:19:27,125 --> 01:19:28,665
He may suffer some limited
chronic kidney insufficiency.

1115
01:19:28,750 --> 01:19:29,790
Here's the report.

1116
01:19:29,875 --> 01:19:31,332
-We don't have time for that!
-RANDALL: She's right.

1117
01:19:31,416 --> 01:19:32,999
-Let's go.
-CAPTAIN SHARP: Stop!

1118
01:19:33,083 --> 01:19:34,707
(LIGHTNING CRACKING)

1119
01:19:34,791 --> 01:19:36,457
Nobody's going anywhere.

1120
01:19:38,625 --> 01:19:40,790
He's not getting
shock therapy.

1121
01:19:41,291 --> 01:19:45,040
That's it!
I am citing you for gross misconduct.

1122
01:19:45,125 --> 01:19:46,374
You are hereby
summoned to appear...

1123
01:19:46,458 --> 01:19:47,624
I'm writing you up back!

1124
01:19:47,708 --> 01:19:50,165
Be notified that
you stand accused of mistreatment...

1125
01:19:50,250 --> 01:19:51,290
What are you talking about?

1126
01:19:51,375 --> 01:19:52,415
I won't let you do it!

1127
01:19:52,500 --> 01:19:53,540
Look!

1128
01:19:54,125 --> 01:19:55,165
(GASPS)

1129
01:19:55,458 --> 01:19:57,040
(ALL EXCLAIMING)

1130
01:20:02,125 --> 01:20:03,790
-They're gone.
-Who?

1131
01:20:03,875 --> 01:20:05,665
-Suzy?
-Sam!

1132
01:20:05,750 --> 01:20:06,790
-They're here?
-Yeah.

1133
01:20:06,875 --> 01:20:09,249
Where'd they go?
Answer me!

1134
01:20:29,375 --> 01:20:31,665
Halt! Stop!

1135
01:20:37,291 --> 01:20:38,582
Stay there.

1136
01:20:38,666 --> 01:20:41,165
Wait, take these!

1137
01:20:55,916 --> 01:20:58,207
Where are you going?
What are you doing?

1138
01:20:58,291 --> 01:20:59,999
Come down!

1139
01:21:13,833 --> 01:21:16,082
Social Services,
do you read me? Over.

1140
01:21:36,208 --> 01:21:37,415
We might have to
swim for it.

1141
01:21:39,375 --> 01:21:41,749
How deep is it?
I didn't bring my life jacket.

1142
01:21:42,208 --> 01:21:44,665
I don't know, but if it's too
shallow, we'll break our necks anyway.

1143
01:21:46,833 --> 01:21:48,207
Hang on to me.

1144
01:21:48,291 --> 01:21:49,499
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

1145
01:21:49,583 --> 01:21:50,832
Okay.

1146
01:21:52,291 --> 01:21:54,499
CAPTAIN SHARP:
No, I'm not married, but I'm a police officer.

1147
01:21:54,583 --> 01:21:56,374
Application denied.
I'm sorry.

1148
01:21:56,458 --> 01:21:58,999
I cannot
authorize that. Over.

1149
01:21:59,083 --> 01:22:01,499
Counselors, what's
the legal perspective? Over.

1150
01:22:02,166 --> 01:22:04,707
In this state,
I would litigate with extreme confidence.

1151
01:22:04,791 --> 01:22:06,540
-I concur.
-Open with Article 1 5

1152
01:22:06,625 --> 01:22:08,040
of the Codes of
Civic Jurisdiction.

1153
01:22:08,125 --> 01:22:09,915
No party,
under any circumstances,

1154
01:22:10,000 --> 01:22:11,499
shall be denied due
and proper consideration

1155
01:22:11,583 --> 01:22:13,040
without prejudice
in perpetuity.

1156
01:22:13,958 --> 01:22:15,124
On three again.

1157
01:22:15,208 --> 01:22:16,374
Wait.

1158
01:22:17,208 --> 01:22:19,582
Just in case
this is a suicide

1159
01:22:19,666 --> 01:22:22,207
or they capture us
and we never see each other again anymore,

1160
01:22:22,291 --> 01:22:25,624
I just want to say
thank you for marrying me.

1161
01:22:26,958 --> 01:22:29,332
I'm glad I got
to know you, Suzy.

1162
01:22:30,375 --> 01:22:32,249
(CHURCH BELLS TOLLING)

1163
01:22:36,083 --> 01:22:37,874
(ELECTRICITY SURGING)

1164
01:22:39,500 --> 01:22:40,707
(GASPS)

1165
01:22:41,916 --> 01:22:43,499
I think you've still
got lightning in you.

1166
01:22:43,916 --> 01:22:44,957
Let's jump.

1167
01:22:45,041 --> 01:22:46,665
No! God damn it!

1168
01:22:49,125 --> 01:22:50,374
Tell him. Over.

1169
01:22:50,458 --> 01:22:52,207
Captain Sharp is
offering to assume

1170
01:22:52,291 --> 01:22:53,957
the responsibility
of foster parenthood.

1171
01:22:54,958 --> 01:22:57,040
He wants you
to live with him.

1172
01:22:57,458 --> 01:22:59,790
SOCIAL SERVICES:
Is this acceptable to you, Mr. Shakusky?

1173
01:23:03,375 --> 01:23:04,624
What do you think, pal?

1174
01:23:15,458 --> 01:23:16,999
We're coming down.
Over and out.

1175
01:23:17,541 --> 01:23:18,957
DELUCA: They're coming down.
Over and...

1176
01:23:20,458 --> 01:23:22,040
(LOUD RUMBLING)

1177
01:23:37,041 --> 01:23:38,999
Don't let go.

1178
01:23:46,416 --> 01:23:48,040
The Black Beacon
storm was considered

1179
01:23:48,125 --> 01:23:49,874
by the US Department
of Inclement Weather

1180
01:23:49,958 --> 01:23:52,832
to be the region's
most destructive meteorological event

1181
01:23:52,916 --> 01:23:55,790
of the second half
of the 20th century.

1182
01:23:56,500 --> 01:24:00,082
It lingered through six high
tides and inundated the islands

1183
01:24:00,166 --> 01:24:03,915
with punishing winds
and extreme high waters.

1184
01:24:04,833 --> 01:24:08,790
On St. Jack Wood,
powerful surges broke the arcade boardwalk

1185
01:24:08,875 --> 01:24:12,165
and demolished
the village bandstand and casino.

1186
01:24:13,208 --> 01:24:15,832
RANDALL: Scout Master's log.
October 1 0th.

1187
01:24:15,916 --> 01:24:18,624
Reconstruction continues
increasingly ahead of schedule,

1188
01:24:19,166 --> 01:24:21,207
which I attribute to
a particularly robust

1189
01:24:21,291 --> 01:24:23,124
esprit de corps
among the troop.

1190
01:24:23,208 --> 01:24:24,415
The latrine, however,
does continue to present...

1191
01:24:24,500 --> 01:24:25,624
Excuse me, sir?

1192
01:24:25,708 --> 01:24:27,665
-You've got the new recruit?
-Yes, sir.

1193
01:24:27,750 --> 01:24:29,290
-What's his rank?
-He doesn't have one.

1194
01:24:29,375 --> 01:24:31,040
Pigeon Scout.
Let's get him a patch.

1195
01:24:31,125 --> 01:24:33,040
NARRATOR: The coastal
areas of New Penzance

1196
01:24:33,125 --> 01:24:35,082
were battered
and changed forever.

1197
01:24:35,166 --> 01:24:36,749
Height.

1198
01:24:37,625 --> 01:24:38,832
63 inches.

1199
01:24:39,416 --> 01:24:42,249
NARRATOR: Mile 3.25
Tidal Inlet was erased from the map.

1200
01:24:44,250 --> 01:24:46,165
But harvest yields
the following autumn

1201
01:24:46,250 --> 01:24:48,957
far exceeded any
previously recorded,

1202
01:24:49,875 --> 01:24:53,665
and the quality of the crops
was said to be extraordinary.

1203
01:24:59,958 --> 01:25:02,540
BOY: (ON RECORD) So you see,
the composer Benjamin Britten

1204
01:25:02,625 --> 01:25:05,124
has taken the whole
orchestra apart.

1205
01:25:05,208 --> 01:25:08,124
Now he puts it
back together again in a fugue.

1206
01:25:08,208 --> 01:25:10,040
The instruments come
in one after another

1207
01:25:10,125 --> 01:25:13,374
in the same order as before,
beginning with the piccolo.

1208
01:25:13,458 --> 01:25:16,624
And at the end, when all the
instruments have finally come in...

1209
01:25:16,708 --> 01:25:19,165
LAURA: Suzy, Lionel,
Murray, Rudy, dinner!

1210
01:25:19,250 --> 01:25:20,665
BOY: ...melody, while
the other instruments...

1211
01:25:21,291 --> 01:25:23,249
WALT: Don't make us
ask twice!

1212
01:25:23,333 --> 01:25:25,124
(RECORD PLAYER STOPS)

1213
01:25:30,666 --> 01:25:32,790
(INSTRUMENTAL MUSIC PLAYING)

1214
01:25:47,083 --> 01:25:48,290
(WHISPERS)
See you tomorrow.

1215
01:26:54,166 --> 01:26:56,165
For Juman

1216
01:27:01,458 --> 01:27:03,874
(CHEERFUL MUSIC PLAYING)

1217
01:29:40,000 --> 01:29:42,415
BOY: Now we will
demonstrate the orchestration

1218
01:29:42,500 --> 01:29:45,207
of Monsieur Desplat's
musical suite.

1219
01:29:45,291 --> 01:29:48,040
A little electronic
metronome sets the time.

1220
01:29:48,125 --> 01:29:49,374
(TICKING)

1221
01:29:49,458 --> 01:29:51,374
First, a harp.

1222
01:29:51,458 --> 01:29:52,957
(HARP PLAYING)

1223
01:29:56,791 --> 01:29:59,374
Next, pizzicato cellos.

1224
01:29:59,458 --> 01:30:00,957
(CELLO PLAYING)

1225
01:30:02,791 --> 01:30:05,790
Flute and piccolo.

1226
01:30:05,875 --> 01:30:08,457
(INSTRUMENTS PLAYING)

1227
01:30:16,041 --> 01:30:17,999
Electric guitar.

1228
01:30:18,083 --> 01:30:20,374
(ELECTRIC GUITAR PLAYING)

1229
01:30:22,625 --> 01:30:23,915
Ukulele.

1230
01:30:24,000 --> 01:30:25,624
(UKULELE PLAYING)

1231
01:30:28,166 --> 01:30:29,790
Classical guitar.

1232
01:30:29,875 --> 01:30:31,624
(CLASSICAL GUITAR PLAYING)

1233
01:30:35,333 --> 01:30:36,874
Banjo.

1234
01:30:36,958 --> 01:30:39,124
(BANJO PLAYING)

1235
01:30:43,166 --> 01:30:44,915
Thin wood blocks.

1236
01:30:45,000 --> 01:30:46,915
(RHYTHMIC TAPPING)

1237
01:30:51,416 --> 01:30:53,374
And two more harps.

1238
01:30:53,458 --> 01:30:55,249
(HARPS PLAYING)

1239
01:30:57,791 --> 01:30:59,457
B-3 organ.

1240
01:30:59,541 --> 01:31:00,874
(ORGAN PLAYING)

1241
01:31:00,958 --> 01:31:02,249
Celesta.

1242
01:31:02,333 --> 01:31:03,957
(CELESTA PLAYING)

1243
01:31:08,958 --> 01:31:10,957
Bowed vibraphone.

1244
01:31:11,041 --> 01:31:13,249
(VIBRAPHONE PLAYING)

1245
01:31:16,000 --> 01:31:17,624
And piano.

1246
01:31:17,708 --> 01:31:19,457
(PIANO PLAYING)

1247
01:31:26,166 --> 01:31:28,374
Pizzicato violins.

1248
01:31:28,458 --> 01:31:30,124
(VIOLINS PLAYING)

1249
01:31:32,041 --> 01:31:33,874
And double bass.

1250
01:31:33,958 --> 01:31:35,790
(DOUBLE BASS PLAYING)

1251
01:31:38,958 --> 01:31:40,540
Tubular bells.

1252
01:31:40,625 --> 01:31:42,457
(BELLS TOLLING)

1253
01:31:42,541 --> 01:31:44,207
